Dialogue: 10,0:01:04.89,0:01:06.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Big America!
Dialogue: 10,0:01:06.66,0:01:08.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Blissful America!
Dialogue: 10,0:01:08.10,0:01:10.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Your favorite America!
Dialogue: 10,0:01:10.07,0:01:13.66,Default,,0,0,0,,The newest American train is being received at this station.
Dialogue: 10,0:01:13.66,0:01:16.67,Default,,0,0,0,,The American Fair is being held here!
Dialogue: 10,0:02:25.24,0:02:29.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Once you eat this, \Nthere won't be turning back! {great, first actual line of the show and I have no idea what she means: if you eat this kind of stuff, you can't take it back - probably "if you accept american products, they'll force more and more of those upon you"}
Dialogue: 10,0:02:29.95,0:02:31.51,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 10,0:02:31.51,0:02:32.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Come with us, you!
Dialogue: 10,0:02:34.06,0:02:35.28,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 10,0:04:07.38,0:04:10.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah! It's that late already? I gotta leave!
Dialogue: 10,0:04:16.49,0:04:18.32,Default,,0,0,0,,You'll be at your best today as well!
Dialogue: 10,0:04:29.56,0:04:32.57,Top,,0,0,0,,Next—Shinjuku! Shinjuku!
Dialogue: 10,0:04:36.64,0:04:37.94,Default,,0,0,0,,American Train?
Dialogue: 10,0:04:37.94,0:04:39.21,Default,,0,0,0,,That's right.
Dialogue: 10,0:04:39.21,0:04:44.47,Default,,0,0,0,,"Big America. Delicious America. Your favorite America," they made that their catchphrase.
Dialogue: 10,0:04:44.47,0:04:47.08,Default,,0,0,0,,It'll run through Harajuku Station on July 4th,
Dialogue: 10,0:04:47.08,0:04:50.49,Default,,0,0,0,,and other places across the country where fairs for American products are held.
Dialogue: 10,0:04:50.49,0:04:52.19,Default,,0,0,0,,50 of them countrywide, it seems.
Dialogue: 10,0:04:52.19,0:04:52.91,Default,,0,0,0,,I see...
Dialogue: 10,0:04:52.91,0:04:57.73,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a major project to promote imports of American products.
Dialogue: 10,0:04:57.73,0:05:02.40,Default,,0,0,0,,So maybe we should also cover it with a major special article in our city.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:02.90,0:05:05.93,Default,,0,0,0,,I wanted to put you in charge of that.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:07.10,0:05:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Me?
Dialogue: 10,0:05:08.00,0:05:08.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:08.90,0:05:12.07,Default,,0,0,0,,You've long been wanting \Nto cover something big, right?
Dialogue: 10,0:05:12.07,0:05:13.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, here's something worth covering!
Dialogue: 10,0:05:14.44,0:05:16.66,Default,,0,0,0,,T-Thank you, editor-in-chief.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:16.66,0:05:18.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Will you help her with the photos, Ishida-kun?
Dialogue: 10,0:05:18.91,0:05:20.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. Pleased to work with you, Yokozawa-san.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:20.65,0:05:21.77,Default,,0,0,0,,The pleasure is mine.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:21.77,0:05:25.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Good. Get to work starting tomorrow, you two.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:25.78,0:05:26.72,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}Okay! {\i0}
Dialogue: 10,0:05:31.68,0:05:33.53,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm very excited about this assignment.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:33.53,0:05:35.36,Default,,0,0,0,,I admire America with all my heart!
Dialogue: 10,0:05:35.36,0:05:39.13,Default,,0,0,0,,I plan to go to California someday to study photography there.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:40.44,0:05:42.74,Default,,0,0,0,,I was dreaming of New York.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:42.74,0:05:45.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Broadway, Times Square, Wall Street...
Dialogue: 10,0:05:46.24,0:05:51.13,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd love to report from the center of world culture and economy.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:51.13,0:05:54.38,Default,,0,0,0,,I sure hope they send me to the US for the next assignment.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:54.38,0:05:56.55,Default,,0,0,0,,That'd be good. I hope so too.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:56.55,0:05:58.65,Default,,0,0,0,,I have a premonition of something.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:58.65,0:06:02.05,Default,,0,0,0,,I feel like the American Train will bring about a major change in us both.
Dialogue: 10,0:06:02.99,0:06:03.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 10,0:06:08.93,0:06:09.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Welcome.
Dialogue: 10,0:06:09.52,0:06:11.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Welcome!
Dialogue: 10,0:06:12.03,0:06:12.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Over there.
Dialogue: 10,0:06:12.84,0:06:13.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Got it.
Dialogue: 10,0:06:15.67,0:06:18.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay, look this way now! Good!
Dialogue: 10,0:06:22.01,0:06:25.85,Default,,0,0,0,,So what exactly is the American Train?
Dialogue: 10,0:06:25.85,0:06:30.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, to put it simply, it's a program to express the goodness of America and American products
Dialogue: 10,0:06:30.85,0:06:35.06,Default,,0,0,0,,in a way that everyone would be able to understand.
Dialogue: 10,0:06:43.30,0:06:46.53,Default,,0,0,0,,I see. Could you explain more specifically?
Dialogue: 10,0:06:46.89,0:06:50.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Starting on July 4th, US Independence Day,
Dialogue: 10,0:06:50.39,0:06:53.40,Default,,0,0,0,,a train converted into a pavilion will travel
Dialogue: 10,0:06:53.40,0:06:57.85,Default,,0,0,0,,through approximately 50 stations, linking sister cities in Japan and the US
Dialogue: 10,0:07:00.80,0:07:06.09,Default,,0,0,0,,We hope everyone will enjoy the pavilions and the events they bring.
Dialogue: 10,0:07:06.09,0:07:10.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Furthermore, there are American fairs held on station platforms and plazas.
Dialogue: 10,0:07:10.34,0:07:12.13,Default,,0,0,0,,These focus specifically
Dialogue: 10,0:07:12.13,0:07:17.33,Default,,0,0,0,,on activities encouraging everyone to purchase various specialty American products.
Dialogue: 10,0:07:23.09,0:07:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So what exactly is the purpose
Dialogue: 10,0:07:26.00,0:07:27.76,Default,,0,0,0,,of this American Train?
Dialogue: 10,0:07:28.50,0:07:33.45,Default,,0,0,0,,That's quite simple! Its goal is deepening the friendship between Japan and the US.
Dialogue: 10,0:07:33.45,0:07:40.76,Default,,0,0,0,,By means of this campaign, we hope to encourage the imports and resolve the current trade frictions.
Dialogue: 10,0:07:47.96,0:07:50.02,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm getting a bit tired here.
Dialogue: 10,0:07:50.47,0:07:51.93,Default,,0,0,0,,That's true...
Dialogue: 10,0:07:51.93,0:07:57.03,Default,,0,0,0,,I understand the meaning of American Train, \Nbut the whole thing honestly feels too gaudy. {exaggerated; bombastic}
Dialogue: 10,0:07:57.03,0:08:02.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, that's what happens when a private project \Ntakes the form of a national sales pitch.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:02.98,0:08:07.54,Default,,0,0,0,,It feels like these American products are just being blatantly pushed on me.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:07.54,0:08:08.88,Default,,0,0,0,,I suppose.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:09.52,0:08:12.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Can't say I don't feel the same way about it.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:12.55,0:08:14.49,Default,,0,0,0,,This stuff is poisonous!
Dialogue: 10,0:08:14.49,0:08:18.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Eating this is like tying \Na noose around your own neck!
Dialogue: 10,0:08:18.39,0:08:20.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Why can't you see?!
Dialogue: 10,0:08:26.10,0:08:28.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Stop it, grandpa!
Dialogue: 10,0:08:28.22,0:08:30.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Stop, you're embarrassing me!
Dialogue: 10,0:08:30.16,0:08:34.40,Default,,0,0,0,,This whole "American Train" \Nis just a gimmicky "kitchen car" stunt. {not "food truck", explained later}
Dialogue: 10,0:08:34.40,0:08:36.07,Default,,0,0,0,,A pompous kitchen car, you hear?!
Dialogue: 10,0:08:36.07,0:08:37.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Kitchen car?
Dialogue: 10,0:08:39.08,0:08:40.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Cool down, gramps!
Dialogue: 10,0:08:41.00,0:08:43.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Quit yelling weird things!
Dialogue: 10,0:08:43.02,0:08:44.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Ugh! Let go!
Dialogue: 10,0:08:44.65,0:08:45.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Grandpa!
Dialogue: 10,0:08:45.92,0:08:48.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey! Aren't you being a bit too harsh to him?
Dialogue: 10,0:08:48.92,0:08:52.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Who are you? \NAre you with this geezer?
Dialogue: 10,0:08:52.03,0:08:53.26,Default,,0,0,0,,No, I'm not.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:53.26,0:08:57.87,Default,,0,0,0,,There are some weirdos out there pulling stunts \Nin protest against the American Train.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:58.43,0:09:00.26,Default,,0,0,0,,You need a permission to take pictures!
Dialogue: 10,0:09:00.74,0:09:02.90,Default,,0,0,0,,I have that permission.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:04.17,0:09:05.56,Default,,0,0,0,,I said no!
Dialogue: 10,0:09:08.94,0:09:10.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you okay, grandpa?
Dialogue: 10,0:09:12.28,0:09:13.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you hurt?
Dialogue: 10,0:09:13.65,0:09:15.72,Default,,0,0,0,,No, I'll be fine.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:15.72,0:09:18.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Some brutes they are. \NTreating the elderly this way!
Dialogue: 10,0:09:18.82,0:09:22.79,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s nothing. I’ve got a strong body from years of working in the fields.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:22.79,0:09:24.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Can't hurt me that easily.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:24.66,0:09:27.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Excuse me, but what made you say those things?
Dialogue: 10,0:09:27.62,0:09:32.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, I came to see this touted American Train \Nbecause my grandson urged me to.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:32.90,0:09:38.60,Default,,0,0,0,,But the way they mocked the Japanese \Nfired me up like nothing else.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:38.60,0:09:40.91,Default,,0,0,0,,I couldn't help getting mad.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:43.51,0:09:45.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Um, one more thing.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:45.60,0:09:49.58,Default,,0,0,0,,What is that "kitchen car" you mentioned earlier?
Dialogue: 10,0:09:49.58,0:09:54.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Hm. Don't you know what a kitchen car is?
Dialogue: 10,0:09:54.46,0:09:57.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. It was actually the first time I heard it.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:57.66,0:09:59.98,Default,,0,0,0,,I've never heard of it either.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:59.98,0:10:03.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Hm. I see, that's understandable.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:03.00,0:10:06.50,Default,,0,0,0,,This term goes back \Nto before you guys were even born.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:06.50,0:10:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,But even if you haven't heard it with your ears, \Nyour body should be well acquainted with it.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:12.00,0:10:13.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Huh?
Dialogue: 10,0:10:14.43,0:10:17.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Look, there's one. Right there.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:22.82,0:10:27.66,Default,,0,0,0,,From about 1956 to 1961, \Nthose foreign kitchen cars traveled all over Japan,
Dialogue: 10,0:10:27.66,0:10:31.68,Default,,0,0,0,,teaching the housewives "nutritious cooking." {https://recipes.hypotheses.org/17642#:~:text=From%201956%20to%201960%2C%20the,importantly%2C%20ingredients%20(i.e.%20American%20agricultural}
Dialogue: 10,0:10:31.68,0:10:34.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Nutritious cooking?
Dialogue: 10,0:10:34.00,0:10:35.50,Default,,0,0,0,,What does that mean?
Dialogue: 10,0:10:35.50,0:10:36.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Hm?
Dialogue: 10,0:10:36.19,0:10:40.64,Default,,0,0,0,,As the name suggests, they cooked nutritious food \Nin those cars to teach the people how to do it.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:40.64,0:10:45.01,Default,,0,0,0,,It was funded from the US, with cooperation from the Ministry of Health and Welfare.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:45.01,0:10:48.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Does the name of Kaya Okinobu \Nring any bell to you? {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Okinori_Kaya}
Dialogue: 10,0:10:48.20,0:10:50.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Kaya Okinobu?
Dialogue: 10,0:10:50.04,0:10:52.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Is that the former Class-A war criminal?
Dialogue: 10,0:10:52.64,0:11:00.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. He was the chairman at Japan Dietetic Association, \Nwhich put this nutritional guidance program into action. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese-style_diet#Achievement_of_nutritional_improvement}
Dialogue: 10,0:11:00.72,0:11:04.16,Default,,0,0,0,,They said if you only eat rice, \Nyou'll be stupid.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:04.16,0:11:05.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}No way!{\i0}
Dialogue: 10,0:11:07.50,0:11:11.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, they did believe it and launched the kitchen cars back then.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:12.37,0:11:15.10,Default,,0,0,0,,It was advertised on every corner. {no clue what's first word}
Dialogue: 10,0:11:15.10,0:11:18.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Let us all eat bread!
Dialogue: 10,0:11:18.66,0:11:22.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Let us all eat bread!
Dialogue: 10,0:11:22.48,0:11:25.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Bread diet is good for your mind and body! {bread-centered diet (as opposed to rice)}
Dialogue: 10,0:11:26.38,0:11:30.69,Default,,0,0,0,,If you only eat rice, \Nyour body will stop developing.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:31.99,0:11:34.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Let us all eat bread!
Dialogue: 10,0:11:34.89,0:11:37.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Bread is good for your mind and body!
Dialogue: 10,0:11:37.91,0:11:41.76,Default,,0,0,0,,If you only eat rice, \Nyour body will stop developing.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:41.76,0:11:45.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Let us all eat bread!
Dialogue: 10,0:11:52.26,0:11:54.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay, let's eat.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:56.01,0:11:58.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, don't feed us the rice alone.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:59.48,0:12:00.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Huh?
Dialogue: 10,0:12:00.67,0:12:04.19,Default,,0,0,0,,They say you turn stupid \Nfrom eating nothing but rice.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:04.19,0:12:05.84,Default,,0,0,0,,What are you saying?
Dialogue: 10,0:12:05.84,0:12:09.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Did you forget how much we treasured \Neven a handful of white rice
Dialogue: 10,0:12:09.29,0:12:12.18,Default,,0,0,0,,during and after the war, \Nwhen there were food shortages?
Dialogue: 10,0:12:12.18,0:12:14.20,Default,,0,0,0,,See for yourself.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:14.20,0:12:18.19,Default,,0,0,0,,You should read the newspaper too, sometimes. \NAt least to keep up with the news!
Dialogue: 10,0:12:18.19,0:12:23.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Huh? "Eating rice inhibits brain development. \NBread diet is recommended, especially for children?"
Dialogue: 10,0:12:23.59,0:12:25.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh my...
Dialogue: 10,0:12:28.24,0:12:32.98,Default,,0,0,0,,And therefore, \Nas I've been explaining for all this time,
Dialogue: 10,0:12:33.60,0:12:36.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Rice weighs heavily on the stomach and is nutritionally unbalanced.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:36.48,0:12:40.54,Default,,0,0,0,,It is harmful to the body \Nand inhibits the work of the brain cells.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:45.48,0:12:52.47,Default,,0,0,0,,And this is how you sandwich the fried flavor between slices of bread coated with ginger miso.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:52.47,0:12:56.50,Default,,0,0,0,,You cut it into pieces \Nand serve it with apples or other side dishes.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:56.50,0:12:59.71,Default,,0,0,0,,And... you can serve it on a fish pan.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:59.71,0:13:04.30,Default,,0,0,0,,With it, they gradually changed the public mindset in regards to eating habits.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:04.30,0:13:11.24,Top,,0,0,0,,The Kitchen Car program was the first concrete program we undertook in Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:11.24,0:13:15.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Our next plans include expansion of school lunches, \Nand development of domestic bread industry.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:15.66,0:13:21.10,Default,,0,0,0,,We focused all of our early market development efforts on Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:21.10,0:13:26.60,Default,,0,0,0,,We specifically targeted Japan and concentrated the US Department of Agriculture aid funds here.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:26.60,0:13:30.97,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result, wheat imports \Nfrom the US increased dramatically.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:30.97,0:13:35.90,Default,,0,0,0,,2.5 million tons in 1960 \Nbecame 5.5 million tons this year.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:35.90,0:13:41.18,Default,,0,0,0,,The share of American wheat has increased from 30% to 60%.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:47.02,0:13:50.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, according to the policy of the Ministry of Education,
Dialogue: 10,0:13:50.18,0:13:54.06,Default,,0,0,0,,we've decided to provide bread-centered lunches to elementary school students first.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:54.06,0:13:57.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Eventually, we plan to extend it \Nto junior high schools as well.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:58.52,0:14:03.97,Default,,0,0,0,,So, the new school lunches came as an extension of the kitchen car program? I didn't expect that.
Dialogue: 10,0:14:03.97,0:14:04.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 10,0:14:04.53,0:14:07.71,Default,,0,0,0,,That man they interviewed, Baum,
Dialogue: 10,0:14:07.71,0:14:13.55,Default,,0,0,0,,later did not hesitate to say that Japanese bread \Ncompanies were developed by America.
Dialogue: 10,0:14:22.16,0:14:26.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Now! Come, come!
Dialogue: 10,0:14:26.23,0:14:30.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Newspapers, radio, magazines, specialized books,
Dialogue: 10,0:14:30.47,0:14:36.99,Default,,0,0,0,,and even prominent scholars and critics, such as Professor Hayashi Takashi of Keio University,
Dialogue: 10,0:14:36.99,0:14:42.91,Default,,0,0,0,,claim that eating rice makes you stupid, while eating bread makes you smarter!
Dialogue: 10,0:14:42.91,0:14:48.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, you heard me right! Please, please! \NStarting tomorrow... No, starting today already!
Dialogue: 10,0:14:48.05,0:14:52.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Replace the rice in your ration fully with bread!
Dialogue: 10,0:14:52.84,0:14:55.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't hesitate to ask us how!
Dialogue: 10,0:15:00.46,0:15:05.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let’s continue with the trending topic \Non the dangers of a rice-based diet.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:05.59,0:15:09.59,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll hear from a prominent \Ncritic Sawada Koichi-sensei.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:09.59,0:15:12.88,Default,,0,0,0,,To bring the average physique \Nof Japanese people up to par with Westerners,
Dialogue: 10,0:15:12.88,0:15:15.54,Default,,0,0,0,,switching from rice to bread is essential!
Dialogue: 10,0:15:15.54,0:15:21.44,Default,,0,0,0,,We need to shift towards a more refined food culture, focusing on health-enhancing foods like meat and eggs. {no clue what's iiyoka there}
Dialogue: 10,0:15:21.44,0:15:24.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Evidence of this can be seen in the low levels
Dialogue: 10,0:15:24.52,0:15:30.19,Default,,0,0,0,,of civilization among many rice-centered societies, \Nmainly those situated in Southeast Asia.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:31.19,0:15:33.86,Default,,0,0,0,,What is this imbecile talking about?
Dialogue: 10,0:15:33.86,0:15:36.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan is the land of the rice ears! {fresh, young ears of rice​}
Dialogue: 10,0:15:36.13,0:15:41.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Tossing out all the rice is the same \Nas asking for divine punishment, goddammit!{actually "punishment from sun [god]"}
Dialogue: 10,0:15:41.97,0:15:48.14,Default,,0,0,0,,But dad, my son also eats bread for school lunch.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:49.11,0:15:52.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Silence! Let's all settle down now!
Dialogue: 10,0:15:52.80,0:15:56.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Both this bread and skim milk powder \Nare American-made.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:56.85,0:15:59.81,Default,,0,0,0,,They say eating bread makes you smarter.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:59.81,0:16:02.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's eat well and leave nothing on the plate.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:02.56,0:16:04.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay!
Dialogue: 10,0:16:06.53,0:16:11.77,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems, the connection between the kitchen cars \Nand school lunches is undeniable.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:11.77,0:16:16.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, but all I remember about school lunches \Nis that they were never any good.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:16.60,0:16:18.66,Default,,0,0,0,,You're right, they're bad, actually.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:18.66,0:16:25.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, before we knew it, we fell in love with bread \Nand forgot the rice. Isn't that right?
Dialogue: 10,0:16:26.78,0:16:27.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah...
Dialogue: 10,0:16:27.38,0:16:29.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Come to think about it, you're right.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:31.25,0:16:35.62,Default,,0,0,0,,When I said that your body remembers what a kitchen car is, that's what I meant.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:37.66,0:16:43.02,Default,,0,0,0,,By the way, do you guys know \Nabout that old movie called Weasel Children? {I actually can't find this one}
Dialogue: 10,0:16:43.66,0:16:46.03,Default,,0,0,0,,"Weasel Children?" Don't think so...
Dialogue: 10,0:16:46.63,0:16:48.70,Default,,0,0,0,,I've never heard of it either.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:48.70,0:16:52.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Figures. It is actually one crappy movie.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:52.34,0:16:58.78,Default,,0,0,0,,But at the time, it was screened extensively throughout the country to promote school lunches.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:12.90,0:17:16.43,Default,,0,0,0,,There were two elementary schools \Nin two neighboring rural towns.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:16.43,0:17:23.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Yama Town's Elementary hadn’t started serving bread lunches yet, so the kids were still eating nothing but rice.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:23.20,0:17:26.77,Default,,0,0,0,,It gave them protruding bellies \Nand a weasel-like body.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:33.05,0:17:36.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, kids in town schools where lunches are already provided
Dialogue: 10,0:17:36.45,0:17:40.32,Default,,0,0,0,,have shown impressive improvement in their academic performance.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:40.32,0:17:45.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Whenever they met the children of the Yama Town, \Nthey made fun of them, calling them weasels.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:48.16,0:17:49.70,Thought,,0,0,0,,In this case... {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,0:17:49.70,0:17:51.83,Default,,0,0,0,,The elementary school teacher in Yama Town
Dialogue: 10,0:17:51.83,0:17:55.00,Default,,0,0,0,,explained the importance of adding bread to school lunches.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:53.30,0:17:55.00,Top,,0,0,0,,Don't you understand? {same}
Dialogue: 10,0:17:55.00,0:18:00.64,Default,,0,0,0,,But many of the parents were rice farmers, who didn't even attend the school lunch information sessions.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:59.31,0:18:02.68,Top,,0,0,0,,You need to have a healthy and balanced diet... {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,0:18:00.64,0:18:03.52,Default,,0,0,0,,A-san, a traditional father,
Dialogue: 10,0:18:02.68,0:18:04.48,Top,,0,0,0,,I don't care!
Dialogue: 10,0:18:03.52,0:18:08.85,Default,,0,0,0,,held firmly to his belief that food prepared by parents can't be bad for their child.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:09.32,0:18:15.89,Default,,0,0,0,,One day, A-san's eldest son, who had just moved to Tokyo to get a job, collapsed due to low blood pressure. {no clue what's actually the disease, keikkaku ?}
Dialogue: 10,0:18:17.39,0:18:22.16,Default,,0,0,0,,A-san was worried that it may have happened \Ndue to unbalanced nutrition.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:22.83,0:18:27.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Then came the day of the inter-town marathon.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:30.83,0:18:32.67,Default,,0,0,0,,And the runners took off! {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,0:18:33.21,0:18:37.76,Default,,0,0,0,,A-san's second son started off strong, but halfway through the marathon,
Dialogue: 10,0:18:37.76,0:18:41.75,Default,,0,0,0,,he ran out of breath and crouched on the ground, despite his father's heated encouragement.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:42.12,0:18:44.82,Default,,0,0,0,,This was enough to convince the stubborn A-san.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:44.82,0:18:47.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Rice and plum bento was no longer good enough. {hinomaru bento}
Dialogue: 10,0:18:48.59,0:18:52.36,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result, the Yama Town school also began serving bread lunches,
Dialogue: 10,0:18:52.36,0:18:55.66,Default,,0,0,0,,and the kids were no longer teased as weasels.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:03.87,0:19:05.87,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't believe it!
Dialogue: 10,0:19:05.87,0:19:08.64,Default,,0,0,0,,There's no way such a stupid movie exists!
Dialogue: 10,0:19:09.48,0:19:12.18,Top,,0,0,0,,Oh no, it really did happen.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:12.18,0:19:16.27,Top,,0,0,0,,The National School Lunch Association was behind all of that.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:16.27,0:19:18.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Hello, Mister Yoshikawa.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:18.62,0:19:21.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes... Hello, Mister John Baum. {I thought he was Richard}
Dialogue: 10,0:19:21.69,0:19:24.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Mister Baum, cinema—OK.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:24.13,0:19:26.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you for the produce money.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:26.04,0:19:29.16,Default,,0,0,0,,By the way, next kitchen car money please? {no clue what's last word}
Dialogue: 10,0:19:29.16,0:19:30.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Would you like 100 more cars?
Dialogue: 10,0:19:30.77,0:19:34.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, advertising... Getting better! Right...
Dialogue: 10,0:19:34.00,0:19:35.67,Default,,0,0,0,,OK, sure!
Dialogue: 10,0:19:38.31,0:19:42.20,Default,,0,0,0,,They screened it like that for quite some time.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:42.20,0:19:43.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Goodness...
Dialogue: 10,0:19:43.38,0:19:45.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Now I wanna watch it too!
Dialogue: 10,0:19:45.71,0:19:48.55,Default,,0,0,0,,That would be impossible, I'm afraid.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:48.55,0:19:52.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Even if there were film reels, \Nthey were never released for public.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:52.65,0:19:55.22,Default,,0,0,0,,They must be mighty embarrassed about it, I imagine.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:55.22,0:19:58.23,Default,,0,0,0,,But was it truly necessary to go to such lengths
Dialogue: 10,0:19:58.23,0:20:03.16,Default,,0,0,0,,to aggressively promote bread-based meals and school lunches?
Dialogue: 10,0:20:03.16,0:20:05.67,Default,,0,0,0,,They were bound by the \NMSA Wheat Import Agreement.
Dialogue: 10,0:20:06.10,0:20:09.66,Default,,0,0,0,,MSA Wheat Import Agreement? \NWhat is that?
Dialogue: 10,0:20:19.58,0:20:26.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, to put it simply, it was a promise that Japan will buy the surplus of American wheat.
Dialogue: 10,0:20:26.22,0:20:32.84,Default,,0,0,0,,At that time, Japan was essentially the US's backyard, making it impossible for us to refuse that imposition. {lit: tribe nation - not exactly a puppet, but I can't think of a way to describe the relationship between a developed and a primitive country}
Dialogue: 10,0:20:32.84,0:20:35.50,Default,,0,0,0,,More like we gladly accepted it.
Dialogue: 10,0:20:35.50,0:20:36.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Unbelievable!
Dialogue: 10,0:20:37.26,0:20:42.80,Top,,0,0,0,,No matter how much we try to dress it up with claims of improving nutrition or refining eating habits,
Dialogue: 10,0:20:42.80,0:20:50.28,Top,,0,0,0,,in the end, the kitchen car program was just a ploy by the US to get rid of surplus wheat.
Dialogue: 10,0:20:50.28,0:20:55.78,Top,,0,0,0,,Then the government-sponsored scientists and the media also jumped on the bandwagon, {/hyped it up}
Dialogue: 10,0:20:55.78,0:20:58.55,Top,,0,0,0,,despite the dubious nutritional evidence.
Dialogue: 10,0:20:58.55,0:21:02.95,Default,,0,0,0,,The people, who knew nothing of this, \Nstarted asking for more bread themselves. {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,0:21:02.95,0:21:09.96,Default,,0,0,0,,At some point, the eating habits and tastes of the Japanese people changed for the US's convenience.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:09.96,0:21:12.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Yep. That's what I mean.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:13.30,0:21:23.41,Top,,0,0,0,,Japanese school lunches will improve your nutritional standards and prepare you for your future adulthood.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:23.41,0:21:29.32,Default,,0,0,0,,They are intended to help children cultivate better eating habits.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:29.32,0:21:35.26,Default,,0,0,0,,It will also help promote trade between Japan and the United States.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:35.26,0:21:41.10,Top,,0,0,0,,Thanks to the nutritional value of the wheat and milk kindly sent to us from the USA,
Dialogue: 10,0:21:41.10,0:21:46.90,Top,,0,0,0,,our bodies have become much stronger than those of children before the war.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:46.90,0:21:49.87,Default,,0,0,0,,It's not just us who's become happier.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:49.87,0:21:54.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Our families have grown to like bread just as much.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:54.10,0:22:03.95,Default,,0,0,0,,I will continue to train my body and work hard with our American friends to build a peaceful world for us all.
Dialogue: 10,0:22:04.45,0:22:07.44,Default,,0,0,0,,I can hardly control my rage!
Dialogue: 10,0:22:13.06,0:22:14.73,Default,,0,0,0,,That's true. So do I.
Dialogue: 10,0:22:14.73,0:22:19.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Hm. If you say so, telling all that to you \Nwas worth my while.
Dialogue: 10,0:22:19.46,0:22:20.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Grandpa!
Dialogue: 10,0:22:21.22,0:22:24.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's go home. I'm hungry.
Dialogue: 10,0:22:24.74,0:22:27.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, I guess I'll go home then. Good bye!
Dialogue: 10,0:22:28.64,0:22:30.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah... Please wait.
Dialogue: 10,0:22:33.28,0:22:36.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Now I know what a kitchen car was.
Dialogue: 10,0:22:36.42,0:22:40.29,Default,,0,0,0,,But why did you call the American Train the second kitchen car?
Dialogue: 10,0:22:40.29,0:22:44.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And why did you call all the foods on display there poisonous?
Dialogue: 10,0:22:44.43,0:22:47.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Could you please explain that to me?
Dialogue: 10,0:22:48.26,0:22:50.80,Default,,0,0,0,,You guys are journalists, aren't you?
Dialogue: 10,0:22:50.80,0:22:56.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Why don't you do a little research on your own, \Ninstead of just writing what you're told as it is?
Dialogue: 10,0:22:57.20,0:22:58.24,Default,,0,0,0,,B-But I...
Dialogue: 10,0:22:58.24,0:23:00.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Post-harvest application.
Dialogue: 10,0:23:00.73,0:23:03.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Post-harvest application?
Dialogue: 10,0:23:03.61,0:23:07.24,Default,,0,0,0,,What is that thing? \NPost-harve... something.
Dialogue: 10,0:23:07.24,0:23:12.74,Default,,0,0,0,,After being harvested, agricultural products are sprayed with pesticides again to disinfect them.
Dialogue: 10,0:23:12.74,0:23:15.74,Default,,0,0,0,,They use pesticides \Neven {\i1}after{\i0} the crops are harvested?
Dialogue: 10,0:23:15.74,0:23:22.16,Default,,0,0,0,,It is to prevent mold and spoilage during long transportation and storage.
Dialogue: 10,0:23:22.16,0:23:25.37,Default,,0,0,0,,You guys should investigate what happens after that.
Dialogue: 10,0:23:25.37,0:23:28.54,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm sure a lot of interesting stuff will come to your attention.
Dialogue: 10,0:23:28.54,0:23:31.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Maybe even some other hidden things \Nthat you don't expect.
Dialogue: 10,0:23:34.26,0:23:36.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Things we don't expect?
Dialogue: 10,0:23:43.94,0:23:46.19,Default,,0,0,0,,American Train, huh?
Dialogue: 10,0:23:46.92,0:23:48.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's go home now.
Dialogue: 10,0:23:48.46,0:23:49.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah.
Dialogue: 10,0:23:49.49,0:23:50.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh?
Dialogue: 10,0:23:50.39,0:23:51.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Whoa!
Dialogue: 10,0:23:51.11,0:23:52.89,Default,,0,0,0,,1,2, rice! {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,0:23:52.89,0:23:54.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Rice!
Dialogue: 10,0:23:54.50,0:23:58.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't let them take away Japan's staple food! {same}
Dialogue: 10,0:23:58.70,0:24:01.70,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 10,0:24:01.70,0:24:04.31,Default,,0,0,0,,We don't want your train! {guess}
Dialogue: 10,0:24:04.31,0:24:06.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}Yes! Go to hell!{\i0}
Dialogue: 10,0:24:06.54,0:24:11.15,Default,,0,0,0,,We don't want their crops, covered in chemicals! {same}
Dialogue: 10,0:24:11.15,0:24:12.98,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}We don't want! {\i0}
Dialogue: 10,0:24:13.65,0:24:19.12,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems, today was only \Nthe beginning of our coverage.
Dialogue: 10,0:24:43.67,0:24:46.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Post-harvest application.
Dialogue: 10,0:24:46.24,0:24:50.68,Default,,0,0,0,,A system when crops are treated with pesticides again after harvesting for disinfection.
Dialogue: 10,0:24:50.68,0:24:55.12,Default,,0,0,0,,This is done to prevent mold and rot during long transportation and storage.
Dialogue: 10,0:24:58.63,0:25:00.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Mariko-san, look what I got.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:00.50,0:25:03.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you! Come on in.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:04.60,0:25:08.52,Default,,0,0,0,,There it is! List of post-harvest pesticides!
Dialogue: 10,0:25:08.52,0:25:10.64,Default,,0,0,0,,More than a few of them!
Dialogue: 10,0:25:10.64,0:25:12.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's see.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:16.84,0:25:20.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Ethylene, nitrogen, \Ncombustion gases, and so forth...
Dialogue: 10,0:25:20.95,0:25:26.22,Default,,0,0,0,,A total of 57 products are permitted for post-harvest use in the United States.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:28.19,0:25:35.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Among them, 15 chemicals are treated as food additives or natural products in Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:35.43,0:25:42.94,Default,,0,0,0,,And six other items are registered in Japan as pesticides allowed for use on imported agricultural products.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:42.94,0:25:48.31,Default,,0,0,0,,This means, 36 items from here \Ncannot be used in Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:48.31,0:25:53.71,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, it is clearly illegal \Nto use these for post-harvest treatment.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:53.71,0:25:57.62,Top,,0,0,0,,And seven of these pesticides have been proven carcinogenic.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:57.62,0:26:03.79,Top,,0,0,0,,I believe the 2,4-D was one of the ingredients in the infamous Agent Orange used in the Vietnam War.
Dialogue: 10,0:26:29.71,0:26:32.95,Default,,0,0,0,,So it's actually "Cheap, delicious, dangerous"?
Dialogue: 10,0:26:32.95,0:26:37.72,Default,,0,0,0,,But how come such a serious matter \Nwas never brought up before?
Dialogue: 10,0:26:37.72,0:26:43.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Good question. The use of pesticides is supposed to be strictly regulated by food laws and standards.
Dialogue: 10,0:26:43.53,0:26:46.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Say, what if they don't thoroughly check
Dialogue: 10,0:26:46.07,0:26:52.13,Default,,0,0,0,,whether the products meet pesticide and post-harvest treatment standards at the time of import?
Dialogue: 10,0:26:52.13,0:26:57.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's see. Pesticides regulated in Japan upon import...
Dialogue: 10,0:26:57.51,0:27:01.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah, there are some for imported cherries.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:01.05,0:27:04.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, if we select pesticides from that previous list...
Dialogue: 10,0:27:06.02,0:27:08.99,Default,,0,0,0,,They're not testing it for pesticides used in the US?!
Dialogue: 10,0:27:08.99,0:27:11.98,Default,,0,0,0,,What is wrong with this country's \Nchecking regulations?!
Dialogue: 10,0:27:12.73,0:27:15.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's go to the port ourselves, Ishida-kun. {/to the schene}
Dialogue: 10,0:27:32.08,0:27:39.89,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1980, Japan's food imports totaled over 3,388,300,000,000 yen,
Dialogue: 10,0:27:39.89,0:27:43.02,Default,,0,0,0,,making it the world's largest importer of food.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:43.02,0:27:48.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Approximately one-third of those imported products come to the port of Yokohama.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:48.19,0:27:51.26,Default,,0,0,0,,We process all sorts of stuff \Nfrom different countries.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:51.26,0:27:55.54,Default,,0,0,0,,For starters—grapefruit, orange, kiwi, and banana.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:55.54,0:28:02.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Beef, pork, vegetables, wheat, soybeans, buckwheat, potatoes, pumpkins.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:02.68,0:28:05.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Even mountain herbs, sometimes.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:18.56,0:28:21.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Wow, you've got everything \Nand the kitchen sink here. {unsure}
Dialogue: 10,0:28:21.63,0:28:24.52,Default,,0,0,0,,I guess that means \Ntofu and miso are somewhere here too.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:24.52,0:28:29.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Even the staple Japanese foods like soba \Nhave to be imported!
Dialogue: 10,0:28:30.07,0:28:33.11,Default,,0,0,0,,What happens to the food that arrives at the port?
Dialogue: 10,0:28:33.11,0:28:35.83,Default,,0,0,0,,First, we let the Ministry of Agriculture's men inspect them. {no clue what's keieiki here}
Dialogue: 10,0:28:35.83,0:28:39.61,Default,,0,0,0,,It would be a problem if any pathogens get imported with the products.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:39.61,0:28:42.68,Default,,0,0,0,,It is also necessary \Nto protect Japan's flora and fauna.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:42.68,0:28:44.75,Default,,0,0,0,,The Mediterranean fruit fly controversy
Dialogue: 10,0:28:44.75,0:28:47.82,Default,,0,0,0,,is still fresh in my memory.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:47.82,0:28:53.49,NarrTop,,0,0,0,,In 1981, a large outbreak of Mediterranean fruit fly, which lays eggs in fruit,
Dialogue: 10,0:28:53.49,0:28:56.63,NarrTop,,0,0,0,,caused extensive damage to American agricultural products,
Dialogue: 10,0:28:56.63,0:28:59.90,Narrator,,0,0,0,,especially grapefruit, mainly in California.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:59.90,0:29:04.24,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The fumigation agent EDB used at that time contains diaphoretic substances.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:04.24,0:29:09.51,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Although discontinued in the US, it was used as a disinfectant on fruit destined for Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:09.51,0:29:12.78,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Large quantities were imported into Japan, \Ncausing a scandal.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:13.31,0:29:16.95,Default,,0,0,0,,And if pests are found, we disinfect again.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:16.95,0:29:18.08,Default,,0,0,0,,By fumigation, right?
Dialogue: 10,0:29:18.08,0:29:19.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:19.02,0:29:22.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, you could say pests, diseases, and fungal rot
Dialogue: 10,0:29:22.66,0:29:28.72,Default,,0,0,0,,are the fate of any agricultural product that spends a long time crossing the ocean.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:34.57,0:29:35.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Here.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:35.04,0:29:35.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Thanks.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:38.56,0:29:44.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Some are fumigated before coming to Japan, \Nbut a lot more only do it after they get here.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:44.47,0:29:48.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Probably 30% for vegetables, 50% for grains.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:48.72,0:29:53.85,Default,,0,0,0,,70% of beans. \NBut the first place goes to fruits with 90%.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:53.85,0:29:55.96,Default,,0,0,0,,What chemicals do you use for it?
Dialogue: 10,0:29:55.96,0:29:58.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Combustion gases and methyl bromide. {actually "producer gases" but idk what he means}
Dialogue: 10,0:29:58.56,0:30:02.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you have any concerns about the chemicals, \Nworking in a place like this? {no idea what she means}
Dialogue: 10,0:30:02.56,0:30:04.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, that's scary stuff, all right.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:04.70,0:30:08.64,Default,,0,0,0,,We have to work amidst the sea of chemicals here, you know.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:08.64,0:30:12.71,Default,,0,0,0,,So we have to take a lot of precautions, \Nespecially for stuff coming from the US. {no clue what he means by mukou / over there}
Dialogue: 10,0:30:12.71,0:30:14.38,Default,,0,0,0,,If the container's from Florida,
Dialogue: 10,0:30:14.38,0:30:20.54,Default,,0,0,0,,it's likely that the concentration of EDB inside is still strong from the treatment over there.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:20.54,0:30:23.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, it's not that easy. \NArriving at the destination {guess}
Dialogue: 10,0:30:23.78,0:30:26.95,Default,,0,0,0,,takes from two weeks to two months, \Ndepending on the item.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:26.95,0:30:30.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, it’s hardly fresh after all that time in transit.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:43.16,0:30:46.01,Default,,0,0,0,,This is salted bracken from China.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:46.01,0:30:48.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Look how rusty the drums are!
Dialogue: 10,0:30:50.58,0:30:54.94,Default,,0,0,0,,It's been accumulating rust here for at least half a year, I imagine.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:54.94,0:30:58.42,Default,,0,0,0,,I wonder if bracken can really hold up \Nthat long, even if it's pickled.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:58.42,0:31:01.84,Default,,0,0,0,,This will probably be turned into a local specialty. {no idea what he means}
Dialogue: 10,0:31:06.86,0:31:11.80,Default,,0,0,0,,How many quarantine stations are there checking imported foods, at the moment?
Dialogue: 10,0:31:11.80,0:31:14.57,Default,,0,0,0,,We have about 20 locations nationwide.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:14.57,0:31:18.11,Default,,0,0,0,,How many of your people are engaged in this work?
Dialogue: 10,0:31:18.11,0:31:20.51,Default,,0,0,0,,We have 75 employees total.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:20.51,0:31:22.61,Default,,0,0,0,,And here, at Yokohama Quarantine Station?
Dialogue: 10,0:31:22.61,0:31:23.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Seven.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:23.71,0:31:28.52,Default,,0,0,0,,I was informed that approximately one-third of imported goods come through port of Yokohama.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:28.52,0:31:31.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet only seven people \Nare supposed to check all of it?
Dialogue: 10,0:31:31.65,0:31:33.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, that's right.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:33.22,0:31:36.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Look at them one by one sounds like a lot of work.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:36.12,0:31:41.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, that's kind of why most of it is conducted through a document review, you know.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:41.16,0:31:42.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Just the documents?
Dialogue: 10,0:31:42.66,0:31:44.72,Default,,0,0,0,,That's about 90% of work. {unsure, maybe "90% of imports"}
Dialogue: 10,0:31:44.72,0:31:49.46,Default,,0,0,0,,After checking the documents, we go there to actually look at it and conduct a sampling inspection. {sequential sampling inspection (with reposition)}
Dialogue: 10,0:31:49.46,0:31:52.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Are there any deficiencies \Nin the current inspection system?
Dialogue: 10,0:31:52.24,0:31:57.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we're doing it according to the law, and we have a lot of knowledgeable and experienced specialists,
Dialogue: 10,0:31:57.08,0:31:58.10,Default,,0,0,0,,so I think it's fine.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:01.10,0:32:07.04,Default,,0,0,0,,That port official seemed quite confident, \Nbut really, he was worried too.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:07.04,0:32:12.06,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems there are many more things happening that we have no idea about.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:12.06,0:32:16.05,Default,,0,0,0,,That's true. Things that would be too shocking \Nfor anyone to see or learn about.{unsure what he means}
Dialogue: 10,0:32:16.05,0:32:19.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. We can't just ignore this hunch. \NWe have to dig deeper.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:19.99,0:32:24.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah... Come to think of it, people carefully browse through
Dialogue: 10,0:32:24.44,0:32:28.54,Default,,0,0,0,,various catalogs for electrical appliances and computers they don't even truly need,
Dialogue: 10,0:32:28.54,0:32:34.15,Default,,0,0,0,,yet remain indifferent to issues that impact their daily lives and could even be life-threatening.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:34.15,0:32:38.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, we seek gratification \Nin being called a savvy consumer.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:39.85,0:32:44.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh man, this is so wrong. \NI feel ashamed of myself.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:44.78,0:32:50.46,Default,,0,0,0,,But having seen it with your own eyes, you realized there's more to it than you can imagine, right?
Dialogue: 10,0:32:51.10,0:32:53.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you for waiting.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:55.54,0:32:56.79,Default,,0,0,0,,L-Look!
Dialogue: 10,0:33:02.84,0:33:05.43,Default,,0,0,0,,It's gotten a little hard to eat, hasn't it?
Dialogue: 10,0:33:06.08,0:33:08.68,Default,,0,0,0,,I cried out subconsciously.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:10.44,0:33:15.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s talk to a few more people to get a fresh perspective on this. {unsure what she really means}
Dialogue: 10,0:33:17.16,0:33:20.56,Top,,0,0,0,,What exactly is the problem with imported food products?
Dialogue: 10,0:33:20.56,0:33:24.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, mostly it's pests, \Npesticide residues, and food additives.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:24.33,0:33:27.29,Default,,0,0,0,,And it's not just chemicals that are dangerous.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:27.29,0:33:29.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Mycotoxins are also a major concern.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:30.24,0:33:35.14,Default,,0,0,0,,To combat this, they have to disinfect and fumigate the products several times over.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:36.41,0:33:42.32,Default,,0,0,0,,And more recently, there's also the radiation from the Chernobyl accident, and so on and so forth.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:42.32,0:33:43.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Even radioactivity?
Dialogue: 10,0:33:43.78,0:33:44.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:44.42,0:33:52.09,Default,,0,0,0,,There is always the risk of radioactive contamination when it comes to imports from Europe.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:52.09,0:33:55.70,Default,,0,0,0,,To they conduct tests to detect radioactivity?
Dialogue: 10,0:33:55.70,0:33:59.70,Top,,0,0,0,,Yes. The government has announced that it will test all lots
Dialogue: 10,0:33:59.70,0:34:06.57,Top,,0,0,0,,for 17 products from 12 countries, including the Soviet Union, for possible contamination.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:06.57,0:34:08.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Were there any results?
Dialogue: 10,0:34:08.86,0:34:11.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. As of June of 1988, {how do they know it if the movie is supposedly from 1987?}
Dialogue: 10,0:34:11.95,0:34:16.85,Default,,0,0,0,,32 food items have been found to have radioactivity levels above the threshold,
Dialogue: 10,0:34:16.85,0:34:18.99,Default,,0,0,0,,and their importation has been halted.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:18.99,0:34:21.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Doesn't that mean we can feel safe now?
Dialogue: 10,0:34:21.04,0:34:24.96,Default,,0,0,0,,No, what we are concerned about \Nis the standard value itself,
Dialogue: 10,0:34:24.96,0:34:30.30,Default,,0,0,0,,the 370 becquerels, \Nand whether or not it is really safe.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:30.30,0:34:34.37,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result, an increasing number of citizen groups \Nare conducting their own inspections.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:36.22,0:34:39.71,Default,,0,0,0,,This means we cannot leave the matter \Nto the government, doesn't it?
Dialogue: 10,0:34:39.71,0:34:45.70,Top,,0,0,0,,Indeed, in times like these, \Nwe have no one to rely on but ourselves.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:45.70,0:34:47.61,Default,,0,0,0,,What do you mean by that?
Dialogue: 10,0:34:47.61,0:34:52.59,Top,,0,0,0,,To give you an example, \Nlet us remember the March of 1988.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:52.59,0:34:58.12,Top,,0,0,0,,Antibiotics have been detected in pork \Nimported from Taiwan and the United States.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:58.12,0:35:03.16,Default,,0,0,0,,It was an antibiotic called sulfadimidine, \Nwhich causes excessive sweating.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:04.56,0:35:07.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet they just continued to import it?
Dialogue: 10,0:35:07.83,0:35:12.57,Default,,0,0,0,,No, financial measures have been taken, \Nbut the real problem came after. {no idea what he means, maybe make it more specifically "the responsible were fined"}
Dialogue: 10,0:35:12.57,0:35:13.77,Default,,0,0,0,,What do you mean?
Dialogue: 10,0:35:13.77,0:35:16.24,Default,,0,0,0,,A high-ranking government official came from the US {unsure, could be "exchange of courtesies"}
Dialogue: 10,0:35:16.24,0:35:19.78,Default,,0,0,0,,and said that from now on the US government will be responsible for the inspections,
Dialogue: 10,0:35:19.78,0:35:24.75,Default,,0,0,0,,and if you have their certificate you will get a free pass in Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:24.75,0:35:27.48,Default,,0,0,0,,The same goes for products from Taiwan.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:27.48,0:35:31.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Although it's us, the Japanese, \Nwho will actually have to eat it,
Dialogue: 10,0:35:31.13,0:35:34.26,Default,,0,0,0,,you need a certificate from a foreign country \Nto have a free hand?
Dialogue: 10,0:35:34.26,0:35:36.96,Default,,0,0,0,,The seller’s interests outweigh those of the buyer.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:36.96,0:35:40.80,Default,,0,0,0,,We can't leave something like this to a third party; history has plenty of examples to back that up.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:40.80,0:35:46.07,Default,,0,0,0,,With the liberalization of imports, \Nregulations on additives are being eased year by year.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:46.07,0:35:48.34,Default,,0,0,0,,This is absolutely unacceptable.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:48.34,0:35:53.78,Default,,0,0,0,,If it came to this, we must collect our own data \Nand conduct the checks ourselves.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:56.85,0:36:01.79,Top,,0,0,0,,This has been particularly closely related to the issue of trade friction in recent years.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:01.79,0:36:05.56,Default,,0,0,0,,The biggest example of that is the major deregulation of 1983, implemented
Dialogue: 10,0:36:05.56,0:36:08.68,Default,,0,0,0,,immediately after a request from the Japan Business Federation.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:08.68,0:36:13.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Could the current issues with importing agricultural products also be a sign of trade frictions?
Dialogue: 10,0:36:13.13,0:36:16.10,Default,,0,0,0,,I believe, the certain connection is undeniable.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:16.10,0:36:19.04,Default,,0,0,0,,However, when we talk about food specifically,
Dialogue: 10,0:36:19.04,0:36:23.46,Default,,0,0,0,,I think the question is whether or not it's acceptable to look at it from the economic point of view.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:23.46,0:36:27.40,Default,,0,0,0,,It is difficult to balance \Neconomy and safety, isn't it?
Dialogue: 10,0:36:27.40,0:36:33.41,Default,,0,0,0,,But then, what do the people who actually produce the crops think?
Dialogue: 10,0:36:33.41,0:36:37.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Their view of agriculture \Nis nothing like anyone else's.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:37.56,0:36:43.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Although we call it large-scale farming, it may be more appropriate to call it a factory rather than a farmhouse.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:43.73,0:36:48.90,Default,,0,0,0,,That's because agriculture is an important industry that focuses on export.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:48.90,0:36:53.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Consider the United States, where agriculture alone offsets the trade deficit caused by large oil imports.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:53.91,0:36:58.51,Default,,0,0,0,,They favor large areas of land, \Nhighly productive and economical management,
Dialogue: 10,0:36:58.51,0:37:02.68,Default,,0,0,0,,and the competitiveness to conquer the international market.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:02.68,0:37:06.59,Default,,0,0,0,,This requires a large amount of agricultural machinery.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:06.59,0:37:11.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Even chemicals that are prohibited in Japan \Ncan be used on rice and grass there.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:11.89,0:37:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,At this farm, feeding etc. \Nare managed by computers.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:16.00,0:37:19.70,Default,,0,0,0,,We can't afford to have someone look after each particular animal.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:19.70,0:37:24.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, it's crucial to stop diseases \Nbefore they can take hold.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:24.80,0:37:28.84,Default,,0,0,0,,For that, large amounts of antibiotics \Nare mixed into the fodder.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:28.84,0:37:35.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Half of the antibiotics used annually in the United States go toward livestock farming.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:35.55,0:37:45.29,Top,,0,0,0,,And in 1987, beef from Australia was found to contain residues of carcinogenic chlordane. {not sure I got the chemical right, more like bilirubin chlorine but bilirubin seems to be just a dye, while chlordane seems to be exactly what they describe it to be}
Dialogue: 10,0:37:45.29,0:37:50.56,Default,,0,0,0,,It was used as a termite control agent \Nin Japan until a few years ago.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:50.56,0:37:55.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Even the most common fruit, \Nbananas, have a similar problem.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:55.07,0:38:00.97,Default,,0,0,0,,The workers on the plantation have to work under pesticides falling from the sky.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:00.97,0:38:06.05,Default,,0,0,0,,This is inevitable for major banana plantations \Nrun by large capitalists.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:06.05,0:38:10.62,Default,,0,0,0,,The locals won't even touch the bananas \Nthat are discarded due to shipping regulations. {unsure what he means - what regulations, why they make them discard the product and why won't locals do it - they don't want to or not allowed to?}
Dialogue: 10,0:38:10.62,0:38:17.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Not even when near starvation, with extremely low wages and exploited through peonizing loan-advance systems. {https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%89%8D%E5%80%9F%E9%87%91 - don't think there's a direct english translation}
Dialogue: 10,0:38:17.46,0:38:22.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Because they are fully aware of the harmful health effects of those fruits.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:22.00,0:38:26.49,Default,,0,0,0,,These stemming from prioritizing productivity and cost-cutting in crop cultivation. {and manifest in their bodies}
Dialogue: 10,0:38:26.49,0:38:31.27,Default,,0,0,0,,So what it boils down to is a fundamental difference in how we see agriculture?
Dialogue: 10,0:38:31.27,0:38:36.50,Default,,0,0,0,,The mindset of prioritizing cost-cutting \Nis what has led us to our current situation.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:41.88,0:38:49.39,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm absolutely shocked that we keep filling our bodies with products made in such an unscrupulous way.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:49.39,0:38:54.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Even the people who grow these bananas won’t eat them, and the origin of the growing site is hidden from us. {unsure what she means}
Dialogue: 10,0:38:54.93,0:38:58.57,Default,,0,0,0,,But we keep eating them without knowing or even trying to know...
Dialogue: 10,0:38:58.57,0:39:00.36,Default,,0,0,0,,No, we're being fed, rather.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:00.93,0:39:05.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Don’t you find it odd that our bodies hasn’t shown any abnormalities yet?
Dialogue: 10,0:39:05.84,0:39:07.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:07.20,0:39:13.13,Top,,0,0,0,,Indeed, a major concern is preventing any abnormalities from developing in our bodies.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:13.13,0:39:19.04,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the truly frightening part would be if that toxicity seeped into our genes.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:19.04,0:39:23.56,Default,,0,0,0,,In that case, it would be our children and grandchildren who suffer the effects.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:24.99,0:39:28.93,Default,,0,0,0,,It begins with plankton and eventually finds its way into the human body,
Dialogue: 10,0:39:28.93,0:39:31.89,Default,,0,0,0,,by which point the toxicity \Nreaches alarming levels.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:35.87,0:39:43.58,Default,,0,0,0,,The number of monkeys born without limbs started to rise after imported grains were added to their diet.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:45.18,0:39:49.42,Default,,0,0,0,,It seemed to suddenly appear \Nas a phenomenon one day.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:49.92,0:39:55.32,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s undeniable proof that the disease was inherited from a contaminated body.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:55.32,0:40:00.49,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't think we have any guarantee that the same won’t happen to humans.
Dialogue: 10,0:40:01.66,0:40:07.02,Default,,0,0,0,,I discovered that the number of children with atopic eczema is actually rising.
Dialogue: 10,0:40:07.02,0:40:09.94,Default,,0,0,0,,As well as children with food allergies.
Dialogue: 10,0:40:09.94,0:40:16.14,Default,,0,0,0,,We can't separate this from the increase in imported crops and food additives.
Dialogue: 10,0:40:46.79,0:40:53.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Can you believe it? We eat this stuff every day, \Nyet they’re so careless about regulating it!
Dialogue: 10,0:40:53.80,0:40:58.74,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't even know \Nwhat I can really eat or drink anymore.
Dialogue: 10,0:40:58.74,0:41:02.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Tofu beans, minced hamburger meat, \Nbread flour wheat,
Dialogue: 10,0:41:02.74,0:41:07.79,Default,,0,0,0,,chicken food and eggs, milk, cheese—\Nwe import everything!
Dialogue: 10,0:41:07.79,0:41:10.03,Default,,0,0,0,,What's worse, all that stuff is harmful.
Dialogue: 10,0:41:10.03,0:41:13.07,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems, the rice is the only thing we still produce domestically.
Dialogue: 10,0:41:13.75,0:41:17.43,Default,,0,0,0,,But how did Japan become like this?
Dialogue: 10,0:41:18.14,0:41:22.33,Default,,0,0,0,,We've left our own stomachs in someone else's hands without a second thought!
Dialogue: 10,0:41:22.33,0:41:26.77,Default,,0,0,0,,I think I understand now—\Nwhat that old man was trying to tell us.
Dialogue: 10,0:41:26.77,0:41:30.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Good grief... Where is this country really headed?
Dialogue: 10,0:41:30.75,0:41:36.29,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems, the MSA Wheat Import Agreement that he mentioned was the beginning of it all.
Dialogue: 10,0:41:36.29,0:41:37.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Come on, Ishida-kun.
Dialogue: 10,0:41:39.23,0:41:40.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't lose your spirits.
Dialogue: 10,0:41:40.83,0:41:43.30,Default,,0,0,0,,We still have a lot of research to do.
Dialogue: 10,0:41:43.30,0:41:48.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Like we still don't know what the old man meant when he talked about "things that we don't expect."
Dialogue: 10,0:41:49.84,0:41:53.26,Default,,0,0,0,,M-Mariko-san, wait for me!
Dialogue: 10,0:41:59.48,0:42:05.02,Default,,0,0,0,,MSA—the Mutual Security Act with the USA, enacted in 1951.
Dialogue: 10,0:42:05.02,0:42:11.62,NarrTop,,0,0,0,,In 1954, the Japan-US Mutual Defense Assistance Agreement was signed, building on the previous act.
Dialogue: 10,0:42:12.56,0:42:14.92,NarrTop,,0,0,0,,Based on the situation on the Korean Peninsula at the time,
Dialogue: 10,0:42:14.92,0:42:17.53,Narrator,,0,0,0,,this became the basis for Japan's rearmament.
Dialogue: 10,0:42:17.53,0:42:20.67,Narrator,,0,0,0,,At the same time, they signed a surplus produce agreement.
Dialogue: 10,0:42:20.67,0:42:25.74,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The section relating to wheat trade became commonly known as the MSA Wheat Import Agreement.
Dialogue: 10,0:42:26.86,0:42:30.21,Default,,0,0,0,,The main contents of this agreement are as follows:
Dialogue: 10,0:42:30.21,0:42:35.05,Default,,0,0,0,,First, the US government sells $50 million worth of American wheat and barley to Japan annually,
Dialogue: 10,0:42:35.05,0:42:38.38,Default,,0,0,0,,which amounts to 18 billion yen.
Dialogue: 10,0:42:38.38,0:42:43.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, 80% of the 18 billion yen, equaling 14.4 billion yen, is allocated
Dialogue: 10,0:42:43.76,0:42:48.06,Default,,0,0,0,,by the Japanese government to pay the US military stationed in Japan in yen. {he makes it sound a little confusing, but basically https://www.city.sukumo.kochi.jp/sisi/107401.html#:~:text=%EF%BC%AD%EF%BC%B3%EF%BC%A1%E5%B0%8F%E9%BA%A6%E8%B3%BC%E5%85%A5%E5%8D%94%E5%AE%9A%E3%81%A7%E3%81%AF,%E3%81%9D%E3%82%8C%E3%82%92%E3%81%86%E3%81%91%E3%81%A6%E3%80%81%E6%B3%95%E5%BE%8B}
Dialogue: 10,0:42:48.06,0:42:52.07,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, it will be deducted from the costs of stationing the US military in Japan. {very unsure, he clearly says "from the price the us mil. should pay to Japan" but factually, Japan was supposed to pay for everything}
Dialogue: 10,0:42:52.07,0:42:55.87,Default,,0,0,0,,The remaining 20% would be provided \Nto Japan by the US government as a bonus.
Dialogue: 10,0:42:55.87,0:43:00.24,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the proceeds will be used to produce and purchase weapons.
Dialogue: 10,0:43:00.24,0:43:05.80,Default,,0,0,0,,A portion of that money will be used to develop markets for American agricultural products.
Dialogue: 10,0:43:05.80,0:43:08.01,Default,,0,0,0,,That's an incredibly sweet deal.
Dialogue: 10,0:43:08.01,0:43:10.77,Default,,0,0,0,,It didn't require Japan \Nto use any foreign currency at all.
Dialogue: 10,0:43:10.77,0:43:14.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, this was a wish come true \Nfor Japan at the time.
Dialogue: 10,0:43:14.52,0:43:18.78,Default,,0,0,0,,We were able to redirect all foreign currency towards industrialization. However...
Dialogue: 10,0:43:19.23,0:43:20.29,Default,,0,0,0,,However?
Dialogue: 10,0:43:20.29,0:43:25.40,Default,,0,0,0,,However, this brought about \Na major pivot in Japan's food policy.
Dialogue: 10,0:43:25.40,0:43:34.47,Default,,0,0,0,,At that time, Japan was in the midst of a five-year plan to boost food production from 1953 to 1957.
Dialogue: 10,0:43:34.47,0:43:37.77,Default,,0,0,0,,They swiftly shifted its focus to importing food.
Dialogue: 10,0:43:37.77,0:43:43.42,Default,,0,0,0,,First, they introduced wheat and launched various campaigns to enhance its image.
Dialogue: 10,0:43:43.92,0:43:45.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Such as kitchen car?
Dialogue: 10,0:43:45.79,0:43:50.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, it was an effort to alter the foundation of our eating habits.
Dialogue: 10,0:43:50.65,0:43:55.65,Default,,0,0,0,,But in fact, it was to increase the wheat consumption, and by extension the wheat imports.
Dialogue: 10,0:43:55.65,0:44:00.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Over time, that movement led to so-called euthanization of Japan's wheat industry.
Dialogue: 10,0:44:00.60,0:44:06.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Come to think of it, you don't see anyone treading on wheat plants anymore.
Dialogue: 10,0:44:06.06,0:44:12.81,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1956, the New Comprehensive Measures for Rural Construction were put forward. {新農山漁村建設総合対策要綱}
Dialogue: 10,0:44:12.81,0:44:15.98,Default,,0,0,0,,In the name of "right production in the right place," there was a push
Dialogue: 10,0:44:15.98,0:44:19.99,Default,,0,0,0,,to shift from grain farming to fruit, vegetable, and livestock farming.
Dialogue: 10,0:44:19.99,0:44:23.66,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result, we became less self-sufficient in grains
Dialogue: 10,0:44:23.66,0:44:28.26,Default,,0,0,0,,and increasingly reliant on imports for soybeans and even fodder grains.
Dialogue: 10,0:44:28.26,0:44:33.23,Top,,0,0,0,,And before we knew it, we became only about 10% self-reliant for wheat.
Dialogue: 10,0:44:33.23,0:44:35.73,Top,,0,0,0,,For soybeans, it's even less.
Dialogue: 10,0:44:35.73,0:44:39.67,Top,,0,0,0,,Now even traditional Japanese flavors \Nare produced abroad.
Dialogue: 10,0:44:41.06,0:44:44.01,Default,,0,0,0,,There's an interesting detail \Nin that previous graph.
Dialogue: 10,0:44:44.01,0:44:48.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Please pay close attention to the year 1960.
Dialogue: 10,0:44:48.48,0:44:51.85,Default,,0,0,0,,The graphs show the most change in the '60s.
Dialogue: 10,0:44:51.85,0:44:56.42,Top,,0,0,0,,Do you remember anything about the year 1960?
Dialogue: 10,0:44:56.96,0:45:01.42,Default,,0,0,0,,1960s... Was that when the Security Treaty​ was extended?
Dialogue: 10,0:45:01.42,0:45:06.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, a new mutual security treaty \Nto replace the MSA accords.
Dialogue: 10,0:45:06.47,0:45:09.44,Default,,0,0,0,,The New Treaty, also known \Nas the 1960 Security Treaty.
Dialogue: 10,0:45:17.08,0:45:19.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Protest the treaty!
Dialogue: 10,0:45:21.75,0:45:24.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Death before enslavement! {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,0:45:28.45,0:45:32.83,Default,,0,0,0,,If the MSA agreement marked the first step, the signing of the new security treaty—
Dialogue: 10,0:45:32.83,0:45:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,which split the nation into supporters and opponents—\Nbecame a decisive second step.
Dialogue: 10,0:45:38.00,0:45:38.93,Default,,0,0,0,,What do you mean?
Dialogue: 10,0:45:38.93,0:45:45.96,Default,,0,0,0,,This treaty entailed our commitment to cooperation with the US not only militarily but also economically.
Dialogue: 10,0:45:45.96,0:45:50.97,Default,,0,0,0,,It was fixed in the so-called economic cooperation clause in Article 2 of the Security Treaty.
Dialogue: 10,0:45:53.15,0:45:58.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Article 2: The Parties will contribute toward the further development
Dialogue: 10,0:45:58.05,0:46:03.79,Default,,0,0,0,,of peaceful and friendly international relations by strengthening their free institutions,
Dialogue: 10,0:46:03.79,0:46:09.43,Default,,0,0,0,,by bringing about a better understanding of the principles upon which these institutions are founded,
Dialogue: 10,0:46:09.43,0:46:12.76,Default,,0,0,0,,and by promoting conditions of stability and well-being. {from https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Mutual_Cooperation_and_Security_between_Japan_and_the_United_States_of_America}
Dialogue: 10,0:46:12.76,0:46:18.04,Default,,0,0,0,,They will seek to eliminate conflict \Nin their international economic policies
Dialogue: 10,0:46:18.04,0:46:22.27,Default,,0,0,0,,and will encourage economic collaboration between them.
Dialogue: 10,0:46:22.27,0:46:27.94,Top,,0,0,0,,The Japan Poultry Association signed a contract \Nwith the American Dekalb Company. {can't find any records of this}
Dialogue: 10,0:46:27.94,0:46:35.86,Top,,0,0,0,,Our Association will not handle foreign egg-laying hens \Nor egg-laying systems other than those of Dekalb.
Dialogue: 10,0:46:36.86,0:46:38.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you, Mister Yoshimura!
Dialogue: 10,0:46:38.44,0:46:40.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, thank you, sir.
Dialogue: 10,0:46:41.33,0:46:45.20,Top,,0,0,0,,Chairman Yoshimura, here are the points of the contract.
Dialogue: 10,0:46:45.79,0:46:51.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Highline will slaughter its hens within the next 18 months, and its roosters within 7 days of the last breeding. {actually something like "7 days after eggs are being put into incubator [assuming the eggs were fertilized I guess?]" but the poultry breeding terminology is too dense for me and I can't be bothered; also not sure I should be using hens/roosters here, maybe "females/males" works better}
Dialogue: 10,0:46:51.84,0:46:53.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Sounds good to you?
Dialogue: 10,0:47:04.55,0:47:07.49,Top,,0,0,0,,Soon, large shipments of Dekalb chicks would begin
Dialogue: 10,0:47:07.49,0:47:10.39,Top,,0,0,0,,departing for Japan from airports across the US.
Dialogue: 10,0:47:10.39,0:47:16.90,Default,,0,0,0,,The similarly, Highline's fertilized eggs were shipped throughout the country from various airports.
Dialogue: 10,0:47:41.09,0:47:46.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Naturally, these changes change the poultry farming in Japan on a very fundamental level.
Dialogue: 10,0:47:46.79,0:47:51.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, traditional free-range chickens \Nlike White Leghorns,
Dialogue: 10,0:47:51.43,0:47:56.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Nagoya Cochins, and others have disappeared altogether from Japanese farmers' gardens.
Dialogue: 10,0:47:57.30,0:48:01.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead, more and more facilities were built
Dialogue: 10,0:48:01.14,0:48:06.11,Default,,0,0,0,,for large-scale growing of Dekalb and Highline breeds imported from the US.
Dialogue: 10,0:48:09.52,0:48:11.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, it wasn't just poultry farming.
Dialogue: 10,0:48:11.51,0:48:17.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Livestock farming, including pigs and dairy cows, \Nwent through a similar process.
Dialogue: 10,0:48:21.49,0:48:27.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Alongside this, imports for livestock fodder also skyrocketed.
Dialogue: 10,0:48:45.24,0:48:51.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Relying almost entirely on imports for resources led to various issues along the way.
Dialogue: 10,0:48:52.12,0:48:53.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Something's wrong!
Dialogue: 10,0:48:53.99,0:48:58.43,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the Newcastle disease, \Nwhich is spreading throughout Japan!
Dialogue: 10,0:48:58.43,0:49:00.27,Default,,0,0,0,,How did this happen?
Dialogue: 10,0:49:00.73,0:49:03.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Through the food. \NThe bird food is infected.
Dialogue: 10,0:49:03.36,0:49:05.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Can't we help it somehow?
Dialogue: 10,0:49:05.16,0:49:07.07,Default,,0,0,0,,No, there's nothing you can do.
Dialogue: 10,0:49:07.07,0:49:08.61,Default,,0,0,0,,N-No way!
Dialogue: 10,0:49:16.34,0:49:22.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Japanese agriculture was gradually choked off, one sector at a time.
Dialogue: 10,0:49:22.29,0:49:27.76,Default,,0,0,0,,And then the process was complemented by the Basic Agricultural Law.
Dialogue: 10,0:49:30.30,0:49:36.19,Default,,0,0,0,,The two pillars of the Basic Agricultural Law were structural improvement and selective expansion.
Dialogue: 10,0:49:36.19,0:49:39.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Structural improvement meant promoting land readjustment
Dialogue: 10,0:49:39.14,0:49:41.03,Default,,0,0,0,,and large-scale mechanization.
Dialogue: 10,0:49:41.57,0:49:46.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Selective expansion meant linking agricultural production to the rising demand.
Dialogue: 10,0:49:46.68,0:49:51.92,Default,,0,0,0,,You cut back on producing crops with declining demand or those that can be easily imported.
Dialogue: 10,0:49:51.92,0:49:56.66,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, it was like reverse protectionism, where imported products took priority.
Dialogue: 10,0:49:56.66,0:50:04.83,Default,,0,0,0,,These changes accelerated Japan's industrialization, propelling it into an era of explosive economic growth.
Dialogue: 10,0:50:09.80,0:50:13.23,Default,,0,0,0,,We're having a very meaningful graduation ceremony today. {/significant/important}
Dialogue: 10,0:50:13.24,0:50:17.11,Default,,0,0,0,,It marks the end of your compulsory education \Nand your entry into society.
Dialogue: 10,0:50:17.11,0:50:22.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan is currently undergoing rapid economic growth, with our industries developing by leaps and bounds.
Dialogue: 10,0:50:22.08,0:50:26.72,Default,,0,0,0,,That's the kind of cutting-edge workplace where you'll soon find yourselves working.
Dialogue: 10,0:50:26.72,0:50:31.89,Default,,0,0,0,,My hope is that when you go to Tokyo, \Nyou'll all become valuable pillars of our society.
Dialogue: 10,0:50:33.88,0:50:37.82,Default,,0,0,0,,As farms underwent restructuring, \Nsurplus labor
Dialogue: 10,0:50:37.82,0:50:42.17,Default,,0,0,0,,shifted to Tokyo and other \Nmajor industrial cities,
Dialogue: 10,0:50:42.17,0:50:46.56,Default,,0,0,0,,which were chronically short of workers during the high economic growth period.
Dialogue: 10,0:50:57.28,0:51:01.51,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s no exaggeration to say that migrant farmers and children
Dialogue: 10,0:51:01.51,0:51:07.01,Default,,0,0,0,,who went through mass employment were the backbone of what would become the Japanese economic miracle. {/farmers working away from home}{employment en masse (esp. of middle and high school graduates from the rural districts during Japan's post-war economic boom)}{/Japan's rapid economic growth}
Dialogue: 10,0:51:14.10,0:51:17.46,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1964, Tokaido Shinkansen begins service.
Dialogue: 10,0:51:20.36,0:51:23.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Also in 1964, the Tokyo Olympics were held.
Dialogue: 10,0:51:28.31,0:51:29.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, in 1969,
Dialogue: 10,0:51:29.94,0:51:32.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Rice Acreage-Reduction Policy began. {https://www.tokyofoundation.org/research/detail.php?id=86}
Dialogue: 10,0:51:43.20,0:51:48.20,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1970, the Japan World Expo was held. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expo_%2770}
Dialogue: 10,0:51:48.77,0:51:50.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Its slogan was
Dialogue: 10,0:51:50.14,0:51:52.07,Default,,0,0,0,,"Progress and Harmony for Mankind."
Dialogue: 10,0:52:02.55,0:52:05.97,Default,,0,0,0,,But the reality \Nof that progress and harmony was...
Dialogue: 10,0:52:10.81,0:52:14.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Dear me, is that what you call \Nprogress and harmony? {no idea what she's so displeased about, maybe there's no irony in this line and she actually says "there was a staggering progress and harmony indeed"}
Dialogue: 10,0:52:23.90,0:52:30.81,Default,,0,0,0,,The period of high economic growth turned out to be a fleeting 12-year dream, cut short by the 1973 oil crisis.
Dialogue: 10,0:52:31.31,0:52:35.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Abnormal inflation, company downsizing, massive layoffs, and widespread bankruptcies
Dialogue: 10,0:52:35.51,0:52:37.52,Default,,0,0,0,,among small and medium-sized businesses. {no clue what's zai before kingyo}
Dialogue: 10,0:52:37.52,0:52:42.15,Default,,0,0,0,,How much have we really gained from high economic growth, and how much have we lost? {hope she means this}
Dialogue: 10,0:52:42.62,0:52:46.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, Japan's agriculture is caught between part-time farming and full mechanization. {no idea what she means: playing cat-and-mouse/going back and forth between ... - this honestly feels like some kind of rebus and what we're seeing-the two cars going different ways-isn't helping}
Dialogue: 10,0:52:46.79,0:52:50.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Large-scale livestock farming is endangered by American-made fodder.
Dialogue: 10,0:52:50.73,0:52:51.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And then also...
Dialogue: 10,0:52:57.54,0:53:00.57,Default,,0,0,0,,In rice-growing areas, for the first time since the end of the war,
Dialogue: 10,0:53:00.57,0:53:03.88,Default,,0,0,0,,rice production dropped by 140,000 tons compared to the previous year.
Dialogue: 10,0:53:03.88,0:53:06.97,Default,,0,0,0,,The rice-crop index is at 87. {my understanding is that it's not measures in percents}
Dialogue: 10,0:53:11.25,0:53:13.89,Top,,0,0,0,,At the same time, the rising exports
Dialogue: 10,0:53:13.89,0:53:18.69,Top,,0,0,0,,of industrial products like automobiles to the US \Nsparked strong opposition from Congress.
Dialogue: 10,0:53:21.09,0:53:25.63,Default,,0,0,0,,As previously discussed, the Japan Federation of Employers' Associations is convinced
Dialogue: 10,0:53:25.63,0:53:31.10,Default,,0,0,0,,that the solution to US-Japan trade friction lies in working closely with the government
Dialogue: 10,0:53:31.10,0:53:35.54,Default,,0,0,0,,to fully liberalize agricultural products \Nand reduce subsidies,
Dialogue: 10,0:53:35.54,0:53:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,ending the excessive protection \Nof the domestic agricultural sector.
Dialogue: 10,0:53:40.00,0:53:46.04,Default,,0,0,0,,The Labor Union Federation Preparatory Committee, \Naspiring to become a national center, believes that
Dialogue: 10,0:53:46.04,0:53:49.92,Default,,0,0,0,,agriculture is excessively protected, \Nand subsidies should be cut significantly.
Dialogue: 10,0:53:49.92,0:53:54.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Additionally, we must fully liberalize agricultural products and increase imports
Dialogue: 10,0:53:54.69,0:53:58.00,Default,,0,0,0,,of cheaper goods to safeguard workers' livelihoods.
Dialogue: 10,0:53:58.00,0:54:00.40,Default,,0,0,0,,This will help resolve the trade frictions.
Dialogue: 10,0:54:00.40,0:54:04.80,Default,,0,0,0,,This is one aspect where we can work together with the company in a cooperative manner.
Dialogue: 10,0:54:08.81,0:54:13.75,Top,,0,0,0,,So... After careful deliberation, we've decided...
Dialogue: 10,0:54:16.18,0:54:22.32,Default,,0,0,0,,We've decided to launch the second phase \Nof measures, restructuring the use of paddy field.
Dialogue: 10,0:54:22.32,0:54:29.13,Default,,0,0,0,,We will take decisive action to reduce fallow land, \Nsetting a target of 677,000 hectares.
Dialogue: 10,0:54:29.13,0:54:31.60,Default,,0,0,0,,If you support it, please vote "yes!" {no clue what he actually says in the last part}
Dialogue: 10,0:54:38.67,0:54:42.21,Default,,0,0,0,,It was around this time when the media started jumping on the bandwagon.
Dialogue: 10,0:54:42.21,0:54:48.87,Default,,0,0,0,,They were abuzz with talk of trade liberalization, acreage reduction, and agricultural overprotection—all at once.
Dialogue: 10,0:54:49.58,0:54:54.25,Thought,,0,0,0,,This is another one of those unexpected things \Nthat the old man was talking about.
Dialogue: 10,0:54:54.25,0:54:56.39,Thought,,0,0,0,,They slowly eroded every root. {/took a slow and steady approach}{to remove obstacles in the way of one's objective; to take an indirect approach; to fill in the outer moat​ of the castle}
Dialogue: 10,0:54:56.39,0:54:58.86,Thought,,0,0,0,,But does the main trunk still hold firm? {/So what about the inner citadel?}
Dialogue: 10,0:55:30.52,0:55:34.09,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, we said that if we die, \Nwe die together. {unsure what she means, maybe commitment to cold war on american side, maybe "if our sectors of economy die, they do it all together"}
Dialogue: 10,0:55:38.66,0:55:41.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Protest the South Korean imports! {no clue what's the first two words}
Dialogue: 10,0:55:41.24,0:55:43.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah!
Dialogue: 10,0:55:43.04,0:55:46.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Protest the agricultural imports liberalization!
Dialogue: 10,0:55:46.17,0:55:50.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan's crops has suffered cold weather damage \Nfor four consecutive years since 1980!
Dialogue: 10,0:55:50.94,0:55:58.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Black rice is endangered by the autumn frost sheen, \Nand we're close to having to import it from South Korea!
Dialogue: 10,0:55:58.05,0:56:02.89,Default,,0,0,0,,But South Korea itself \Nhasn't yet reached full self-sufficiency in rice!
Dialogue: 10,0:56:02.89,0:56:09.26,Default,,0,0,0,,So they’re importing rice from America first, \Nthen selling it to Japan!
Dialogue: 10,0:56:09.26,0:56:14.97,Default,,0,0,0,,The political and financial worlds, along with sympathetic factory workers and the media, are all in sync! {actually "labor world" but I think he means factory workers as opposed to farmers, as in communism lol}
Dialogue: 10,0:56:14.97,0:56:17.40,Default,,0,0,0,,They say Japan doesn’t need \Nto produce its own food! {unsure he means this}
Dialogue: 10,0:56:17.40,0:56:23.01,Default,,0,0,0,,They say it’s fine to import rice, fruits, meat, and vegetables—everything but the kitchen sink!
Dialogue: 10,0:56:23.01,0:56:25.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you agree with that, everyone?! {/think that's okay?}
Dialogue: 10,0:56:25.57,0:56:30.45,Top,,0,0,0,,As a result, Japan’s food self-sufficiency rate \Nsteadily declined over the years.
Dialogue: 10,0:56:30.45,0:56:35.51,Top,,0,0,0,,Among all developed countries, Japan was the only one \Nwith a food self-sufficiency rate in the red.
Dialogue: 10,0:56:37.41,0:56:39.42,Thought,,0,0,0,,1986.
Dialogue: 10,0:56:39.42,0:56:43.26,Thought,,0,0,0,,That was when the US pushed Japan \Nto make a decisive choice.
Dialogue: 10,0:56:43.26,0:56:46.36,Thought,,0,0,0,,Namely—uncompromised liberalization of agricultural products.
Dialogue: 10,0:56:46.36,0:56:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, as you likely know, \NJapan is one of the world's largest economies.
Dialogue: 10,0:56:52.00,0:56:56.58,Default,,0,0,0,,We now have a trade surplus of $82 billion.
Dialogue: 10,0:56:56.58,0:56:57.98,Default,,0,0,0,,A staggering number!
Dialogue: 10,0:56:57.98,0:57:01.81,Default,,0,0,0,,This is thanks to Japan's exports of automobiles and home appliances.
Dialogue: 10,0:57:01.81,0:57:05.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan compensated for its lack \Nof natural resources by developing
Dialogue: 10,0:57:05.89,0:57:09.69,Default,,0,0,0,,advanced technology and exporting high-quality industrial products.
Dialogue: 10,0:57:09.69,0:57:15.94,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s only natural that our American partners are now pushing for the full liberalization of agricultural products.
Dialogue: 10,0:57:15.94,0:57:17.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Only natural!
Dialogue: 10,0:57:17.36,0:57:20.22,Default,,0,0,0,,After all, the US is Japan's \Nmost valued customer.
Dialogue: 10,0:57:20.22,0:57:21.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Most valued!
Dialogue: 10,0:57:21.53,0:57:25.17,Default,,0,0,0,,And they also need some assurance of cooperation from Japan. {unsure}
Dialogue: 10,0:57:25.17,0:57:30.34,Default,,0,0,0,,If we want to stay on good terms with our most valued customer, we need to liberalize agricultural products.
Dialogue: 10,0:57:30.34,0:57:34.38,Default,,0,0,0,,For a country as small as Japan, there's nothing wrong with abandoning farming altogether.
Dialogue: 10,0:57:34.38,0:57:38.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Fruits, beef, rice—\Nwe can import {\i1}anything{\i0} from abroad!
Dialogue: 10,0:57:38.28,0:57:41.79,Default,,0,0,0,,There's nothing wrong \Nwith importing it! Absolutely!
Dialogue: 10,0:57:41.79,0:57:47.23,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, it would allow us to enjoy products that are both cheaper and tastier than what we have now.
Dialogue: 10,0:57:47.23,0:57:51.13,Default,,0,0,0,,As you can see, agricultural liberalization \Nbrings only advantages. {guess}
Dialogue: 10,0:57:51.13,0:57:52.99,Default,,0,0,0,,I guess I got carried away a bit. {actually just says "I wonder if it's too long"}
Dialogue: 10,0:57:52.99,0:57:55.40,Default,,0,0,0,,With sincere regret, I have to inform you that
Dialogue: 10,0:57:55.40,0:57:58.76,Default,,0,0,0,,there are only two days left until the Prime Minister leaves for America.
Dialogue: 10,0:57:58.76,0:58:05.03,Default,,0,0,0,,We found ourselves unable to stop the expansion of Cargill Inc. into Shibushi Bay in Kagoshima.
Dialogue: 10,0:58:05.03,0:58:10.00,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Cargill is one of the six largest grain trading companies in the USA, the so-called Big League.
Dialogue: 10,0:58:10.00,0:58:14.35,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The company's sphere of interests spans all grain-related operations,
Dialogue: 10,0:58:14.35,0:58:18.29,Narrator,,0,0,0,,from trading to processing, production, and financing.
Dialogue: 10,0:58:18.29,0:58:21.63,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It has a presence in most countries \Nexcept the communist bloc.
Dialogue: 10,0:58:21.63,0:58:24.99,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It is truly nothing short of a trading company giant. {actually "Without any shame"}
Dialogue: 10,0:58:25.46,0:58:30.84,Top,,0,0,0,,The actions of Cargill Inc. in Shibushi Bay epitomize America's grain strategy toward Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:58:30.84,0:58:34.07,Top,,0,0,0,,They already have feed mills and fertilizer plants in the area. {unsure waht she means}
Dialogue: 10,0:58:34.07,0:58:38.98,Top,,0,0,0,,Will Japan's agriculture become just another asset in this capitalist web? {keiretsu (group); conglomeration of businesses linked by cross-shareholdings}
Dialogue: 10,0:58:38.98,0:58:41.91,Default,,0,0,0,,We can look at Taiwan for answers.
Dialogue: 10,0:58:41.91,0:58:44.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Cargill is the leader of Taiwan's feed industry.
Dialogue: 10,0:58:44.88,0:58:49.42,Default,,0,0,0,,In particular, pig farming has been transformed into an export-oriented business, where everything
Dialogue: 10,0:58:49.42,0:58:53.19,Default,,0,0,0,,from feed supply to management structure \Nis primarily focused on Japan. {unsure how this works or what she means, no clue what's last word}
Dialogue: 10,0:58:53.19,0:58:56.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, their mainstay is beef and broilers. {actually 牛肉ブロイラー is clearly "beef broilers" but that's not a thing even in japanese so idk what they were smokiong}
Dialogue: 10,0:58:56.59,0:58:59.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Is that the future that awaits Japan too?
Dialogue: 10,0:59:02.52,0:59:05.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan must make a historical transition.
Dialogue: 10,0:59:05.74,0:59:08.51,Default,,0,0,0,,I intend to stand up to this challenge.
Dialogue: 10,0:59:08.51,0:59:16.25,Top,,0,0,0,,To resolve current trade tensions with the US, I pledge to my good friend President Reagan that I will strive
Dialogue: 10,0:59:16.25,0:59:21.54,Top,,0,0,0,,to shift Japan's industrial structure from a major exporter to a major importer.
Dialogue: 10,0:59:23.32,0:59:30.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Then came the so-called Maekawa Report, put together by Prime Minister Nakasone's advisory panel.
Dialogue: 10,0:59:39.40,0:59:43.04,Default,,0,0,0,,The Maekawa report \Nwas submitted to the Tokyo Summit.
Dialogue: 10,0:59:43.04,0:59:47.08,Top,,0,0,0,,As a result, the Maekawa Report's call for agricultural product liberalization
Dialogue: 10,0:59:47.08,0:59:49.95,Top,,0,0,0,,became an official commitment of the Japanese government.
Dialogue: 10,0:59:53.25,0:59:59.76,Top,,0,0,0,,And finally, in September, voices demanding the liberalization of rice came out in force. {rice could also mean the US}
Dialogue: 10,0:59:59.76,1:00:05.26,Default,,0,0,0,,RMA—American Rice Millers' Association \Nfiles lawsuit against the US government
Dialogue: 10,1:00:05.26,1:00:09.27,Default,,0,0,0,,However, it seems this was also influenced \Nby someone pulling the strings. {actually "there was someone working in the shadows behind it" - no idea how could someone do that for an open lawsuit against the us govt., but I can't find the said lawsuit itself as well so what do I know}
Dialogue: 10,1:00:12.84,1:00:16.10,Thought,,0,0,0,,This was their new feint to eliminate Japanese agriculture once and for all. {no clue what's shinichi}
Dialogue: 10,1:00:16.84,1:00:20.11,Thought,,0,0,0,,Wheat import dependence is at 86%.
Dialogue: 10,1:00:20.11,1:00:22.81,ThouTop,,0,0,0,,Soybean import dependence—92%.
Dialogue: 10,1:00:22.81,1:00:26.02,ThouTop,,0,0,0,,And if we liberalize the rice as well...
Dialogue: 10,1:00:26.02,1:00:30.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Lemme tell you something, \NJapanese rice is already ridiculously expensive.
Dialogue: 10,1:00:30.12,1:00:35.43,Default,,0,0,0,,The only way forward now is to lift import restrictions \Nand set prices on an international level
Dialogue: 10,1:00:35.43,1:00:38.06,Default,,0,0,0,,to make it available to consumers. {unsure}
Dialogue: 10,1:00:38.06,1:00:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese people will also feel their consumer basket getting cheaper.{lit: food expenses will drop drastically}
Dialogue: 10,1:00:42.00,1:00:45.84,Default,,0,0,0,,What's more, we'll be able to spend more money on other products.
Dialogue: 10,1:00:45.84,1:00:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll enter the era of splurging, \Nand it won't be a dream! {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,1:00:48.91,1:00:51.04,Default,,0,0,0,,That's what I want to scream to all of you!
Dialogue: 10,1:00:51.04,1:00:52.97,Default,,0,0,0,,But I guess I got carried away again.
Dialogue: 10,1:00:52.97,1:00:57.97,Default,,0,0,0,,If rice is liberalized, will it really become cheaper as the critics say?
Dialogue: 10,1:00:57.97,1:01:05.69,NarrTop,,0,0,0,,Only 4% of the world's rice production is exported \Nand available on international markets.
Dialogue: 10,1:01:05.69,1:01:09.26,NarrTop,,0,0,0,,Moreover, if we look at Thailand, the world's largest rice exporter,
Dialogue: 10,1:01:09.26,1:01:14.07,NarrTop,,0,0,0,,there has been a 17% fluctuation \Nin harvests over the past decade.
Dialogue: 10,1:01:14.07,1:01:19.27,NarrTop,,0,0,0,,If Japan, whose staple food is rice, were to step in to buy rice in such an unstable market,
Dialogue: 10,1:01:19.27,1:01:22.47,NarrTop,,0,0,0,,that would obvious drive the international price up.
Dialogue: 10,1:01:22.96,1:01:25.84,Top,,0,0,0,,The rice liberalization will be achieved at all costs!
Dialogue: 10,1:01:25.84,1:01:27.95,Top,,0,0,0,,The US now has a surplus of rice.
Dialogue: 10,1:01:27.95,1:01:31.52,Default,,0,0,0,,While I can't guarantee that the supply will remain steady in the future,
Dialogue: 10,1:01:31.52,1:01:34.64,Default,,0,0,0,,as I am merely the vice president of a private organization,
Dialogue: 10,1:01:34.64,1:01:37.46,Default,,0,0,0,,even if exports from the US were to halt,
Dialogue: 10,1:01:37.46,1:01:42.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan could purchase rice from other countries like China, Taiwan, South Korea, and Australia!
Dialogue: 10,1:01:42.88,1:01:47.57,Top,,0,0,0,,However, only the USA produces Japonica rice, \Nfavored by the Japanese.
Dialogue: 10,1:01:47.57,1:01:51.54,Top,,0,0,0,,Furthermore, other Asian countries are not self-sufficient in rice either. {unsure}{/the exports would have to be shared between various Asian countries}
Dialogue: 10,1:01:51.54,1:01:55.86,Top,,0,0,0,,In the end, this so-called liberalization essentially just means importing from the USA.
Dialogue: 10,1:01:55.86,1:02:01.70,Top,,0,0,0,,And only the few grain majors \Ncontrol nearly 90% of US grain exports.
Dialogue: 10,1:02:01.70,1:02:08.62,Top,,0,0,0,,Ultimately, the price of the rice we purchase \Nis simply manipulated by the whims of big capital.
Dialogue: 10,1:02:08.62,1:02:13.32,Top,,0,0,0,,What's worse, American agriculture is now stuck in a perpetual crisis that's nothing short of a depression.{unsure what she means by "what could be called a financial panic"}
Dialogue: 10,1:02:13.32,1:02:19.83,Top,,0,0,0,,Continuous drought, soil desertification, \Nand rising debts from failed economic policies
Dialogue: 10,1:02:19.83,1:02:23.94,Top,,0,0,0,,are now reportedly causing up to 2,000 farming families to go bankrupt each day.
Dialogue: 10,1:02:23.94,1:02:30.11,Top,,0,0,0,,That's likely why they had to pivot to rice, \Nthe backbone of Japanese agriculture.
Dialogue: 10,1:02:30.11,1:02:35.18,Top,,0,0,0,,It's incredibly foolish to rely entirely on a country like that to feed the Japanese people.
Dialogue: 10,1:02:38.62,1:02:43.76,Default,,0,0,0,,I would like to announce the results of the deliberations \Nof the Agricultural Policy Council.
Dialogue: 10,1:02:43.76,1:02:50.56,Default,,0,0,0,,First: lower domestic food self-sufficiency \Nto ease trade friction.
Dialogue: 10,1:02:50.56,1:02:56.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Second: cut the rice-producing area by 770,000 hectares next year.
Dialogue: 10,1:02:57.56,1:03:02.37,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The self-destruction of Japanese agriculture was happening with small steps like that.
Dialogue: 10,1:03:02.37,1:03:05.28,Narrator,,0,0,0,,If agriculture dies, nature also dies.
Dialogue: 10,1:03:05.28,1:03:10.65,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Paddy fields don’t just produce rice; \Nthey also play an irreplaceable role in flood control.
Dialogue: 10,1:03:10.65,1:03:17.49,Narrator,,0,0,0,,If Japan fully opened its market to the US, one-third of its rice paddies would vanish.
Dialogue: 10,1:03:17.49,1:03:20.99,Narrator,,0,0,0,,We will also have to endure the consequences of soil erosion
Dialogue: 10,1:03:20.99,1:03:24.30,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and water shortages impacting our countryside.
Dialogue: 10,1:03:25.00,1:03:27.43,Default,,0,0,0,,How can they be that foolish?!
Dialogue: 10,1:03:27.43,1:03:29.20,Default,,0,0,0,,It's not just them.
Dialogue: 10,1:03:29.20,1:03:33.90,Default,,0,0,0,,We were the ones who chose those people \Nand entrusted them with Japan's future.
Dialogue: 10,1:03:33.90,1:03:35.37,Default,,0,0,0,,We did ourselves.
Dialogue: 10,1:03:35.37,1:03:36.43,Default,,0,0,0,,A-Are you sure? {no idea}
Dialogue: 10,1:03:37.11,1:03:40.58,Default,,0,0,0,,I welcome our many guests, \Nyou can call me Noboru! {https://web.archive.org/web/20180130154417/https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/16/opinion/ron-and-noboru-a-good-start.html}
Dialogue: 10,1:03:40.58,1:03:43.58,Default,,0,0,0,,To everyone's delight, \Nthe Beef-Orange issue has been resolved. {codename for negotiations in food trade frictions}
Dialogue: 10,1:03:43.58,1:03:47.19,Default,,0,0,0,,I made the decision and put it into action. \NThank you.
Dialogue: 10,1:03:47.19,1:03:51.02,Default,,0,0,0,,You can call me Ron, I am also very happy with this development.
Dialogue: 10,1:03:51.02,1:03:55.20,Default,,0,0,0,,I am pleased to see the resolution of three key issues: the opening of the construction market,
Dialogue: 10,1:03:55.20,1:03:57.66,Default,,0,0,0,,the scientific and technological \Ncooperation agreement,
Dialogue: 10,1:03:57.66,1:04:00.22,Default,,0,0,0,,and the liberalization of beef and orange imports. Thank you.
Dialogue: 10,1:04:00.22,1:04:04.26,Top,,0,0,0,,Thank you very much for taking the time out of your busy schedule to come here today.
Dialogue: 10,1:04:04.26,1:04:06.77,Default,,0,0,0,,The Toronto Summit was a great success,
Dialogue: 10,1:04:06.77,1:04:10.11,Default,,0,0,0,,and the challenging issue of liberalizing beef and orange imports was resolved.
Dialogue: 10,1:04:10.11,1:04:13.44,Default,,0,0,0,,The Ron-Noboru union \Nis now entering its honeymoon season.
Dialogue: 10,1:04:13.44,1:04:16.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, with the full cooperation of JR East,
Dialogue: 10,1:04:16.52,1:04:21.19,Default,,0,0,0,,we can now discuss the American Train program, an express train filled with American dreams.
Dialogue: 10,1:04:21.19,1:04:25.19,Default,,0,0,0,,A word to Okita-sensei, \Nthe Chairman of the Committee.
Dialogue: 10,1:04:25.19,1:04:26.56,Default,,0,0,0,,The project was initiated
Dialogue: 10,1:04:26.56,1:04:31.60,Default,,0,0,0,,at the urging of prominent figures concerned about the rising trade friction between the US and Japan.
Dialogue: 10,1:04:31.60,1:04:34.37,Default,,0,0,0,,It will be a jointly-funded endeavor. {/by Japanese and US companies}
Dialogue: 10,1:04:34.37,1:04:39.36,Default,,0,0,0,,A 12-car pavilion train \Nloaded with American produce.
Dialogue: 10,1:04:39.36,1:04:44.14,Default,,0,0,0,,It will depart from Tokyo and travel through various regions of eastern Japan and Hokkaido for one year.
Dialogue: 10,1:04:44.14,1:04:50.45,Default,,0,0,0,,We must make this a great success and eventually expand it to JR West.
Dialogue: 10,1:04:50.45,1:04:56.39,Default,,0,0,0,,But the problem is this tape, distributed by some individuals "Would you still eat it?" {no idea what's zenchuu - seems to be some activist organization, no idea what's kikakushita - under what plan and what does it mean? doesn't seem like this thing existed in real life}
Dialogue: 10,1:04:56.39,1:05:02.36,Default,,0,0,0,,This infuriated the American political and business circles, including Agriculture Minister Lyng.
Dialogue: 10,1:05:02.36,1:05:07.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Its content sharply criticizes the toxicity of American agricultural products.
Dialogue: 10,1:05:07.03,1:05:09.90,Default,,0,0,0,,For that reason, we need the media on our side. {unsure what he means, maybe "They're trying to draw the media's attention to it." but more likely "bribe media to cover this up"}
Dialogue: 10,1:05:09.90,1:05:12.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Avoid topics of safety and freshness \Nwhenever you can.
Dialogue: 10,1:05:12.97,1:05:16.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Center the promotion around \N"cheap and delicious" as the key theme
Dialogue: 10,1:05:16.71,1:05:22.21,Default,,0,0,0,,to alleviate trade friction, all while celebrating Japan's status as having the world's largest trade surplus.
Dialogue: 10,1:05:24.32,1:05:28.75,Default,,0,0,0,,So our investigation \Nfinally reached the American Train. {meaning unraveling this knot, this film essentially}
Dialogue: 10,1:05:28.75,1:05:32.78,Default,,0,0,0,,I can now see through the unscrupulous trick of the American Train. {lit: I finally understand the open/blatant/crude structure/contrivance/plot of the AT - not sure what he means, even less how to word it}
Dialogue: 10,1:05:32.78,1:05:35.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Ishida-kun, I'll do it.
Dialogue: 10,1:05:35.28,1:05:37.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Huh? What?
Dialogue: 10,1:05:37.29,1:05:40.75,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll write the truth \Nabout the American Train.
Dialogue: 10,1:05:55.01,1:05:56.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Editor-in-Chief.
Dialogue: 10,1:05:56.35,1:05:56.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh!
Dialogue: 10,1:05:57.25,1:05:59.64,Default,,0,0,0,,The American Train article is finished.
Dialogue: 10,1:06:00.22,1:06:04.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh! You sure took your time \Nwith it, didn't you? Let's see.
Dialogue: 10,1:06:06.73,1:06:08.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Wh-What is this nonsense?!
Dialogue: 10,1:06:09.99,1:06:16.50,Default,,0,0,0,,"American Train is the Second Kitchen Car, \Nthe Vanguard of Rice-Crushing?!" {/pioneer}
Dialogue: 10,1:06:17.94,1:06:19.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you out of your mind?!
Dialogue: 10,1:06:20.31,1:06:21.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, you heard me right.
Dialogue: 10,1:06:21.91,1:06:25.01,Default,,0,0,0,,I am confident that we \Nhave done our best job.
Dialogue: 10,1:06:25.41,1:06:28.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Ugh, fine. \NI'll read it just in case.
Dialogue: 10,1:06:32.98,1:06:35.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Did you really think \Nwe could print something like this?
Dialogue: 10,1:06:40.99,1:06:42.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Rewrite it!
Dialogue: 10,1:06:42.18,1:06:44.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Without any of this bullshit! {lit: not even close}
Dialogue: 10,1:06:44.12,1:06:45.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Why's that?!
Dialogue: 10,1:06:45.80,1:06:51.04,Default,,0,0,0,,We faithfully and accurately compiled the information \Nthat emerged during our investigation.
Dialogue: 10,1:06:51.04,1:06:52.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet you can's accept it?
Dialogue: 10,1:06:52.70,1:06:55.97,Default,,0,0,0,,If you're gonna reject it, \Nat least tell us the reason!
Dialogue: 10,1:06:56.44,1:06:59.08,Default,,0,0,0,,What can't you understand?! {unsure, maybe "you got it all wrong"}
Dialogue: 10,1:06:59.08,1:07:05.18,Default,,0,0,0,,What I asked you to write was a showcase \Nof the abundant products that the American Train
Dialogue: 10,1:07:05.18,1:07:09.88,Default,,0,0,0,,introduces and demonstrates, \Nnot this deranged rambling! {no clue what's bakuruginya here}
Dialogue: 10,1:07:10.69,1:07:13.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Why didn't you say it clearly, then?!
Dialogue: 10,1:07:13.19,1:07:16.82,Default,,0,0,0,,What you really wanted was just a puff piece for the American Train! {puff piece (in a newspaper, etc.); flatteringly exaggerated article; sycophantic article​}
Dialogue: 10,1:07:17.26,1:07:19.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Wh-Whadja say?
Dialogue: 10,1:07:19.72,1:07:23.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Just like all the other media, riding on the government’s and financial world’s coattails,
Dialogue: 10,1:07:23.90,1:07:26.66,Default,,0,0,0,,churning out sycophantic articles.
Dialogue: 10,1:07:26.66,1:07:31.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, no one realizes just how toxic the imported products and food additives really are.
Dialogue: 10,1:07:31.71,1:07:37.48,Default,,0,0,0,,What's worse, it's reached the point where they're even importing rice—our staple food—and trying
Dialogue: 10,1:07:37.48,1:07:39.55,Default,,0,0,0,,to wipe out our agriculture entirely!
Dialogue: 10,1:07:39.55,1:07:41.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn't that the great duty of the media...
Dialogue: 10,1:07:41.42,1:07:43.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Fine! Enough!
Dialogue: 10,1:07:43.22,1:07:44.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't rewrite it!
Dialogue: 10,1:07:44.92,1:07:47.36,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll just get someone else to write this article!
Dialogue: 10,1:07:47.36,1:07:51.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Very well. \NI have no intention of rewriting it either.
Dialogue: 10,1:07:51.25,1:07:53.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Excuse me.
Dialogue: 10,1:07:55.13,1:07:56.20,Default,,0,0,0,,M-Mariko-san!
Dialogue: 10,1:07:58.37,1:08:00.04,Default,,0,0,0,,What insolence! {/what's going on/what a thing}
Dialogue: 10,1:08:02.41,1:08:03.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Mariko-san!
Dialogue: 10,1:08:04.91,1:08:08.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Mariko-san, what are you going to do now?
Dialogue: 10,1:08:08.64,1:08:12.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't know yet. \NBut it's definitely not working here.
Dialogue: 10,1:08:20.69,1:08:21.89,Default,,0,0,0,,God!
Dialogue: 10,1:08:57.76,1:09:02.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Once you eat this, \Nthere won't be turning back!
Dialogue: 10,1:09:17.88,1:09:21.87,Default,,0,0,0,,I wonder where this country is headed?
Dialogue: 10,1:09:21.87,1:09:23.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Living in darkness, {lit: only know nothing}
Dialogue: 10,1:09:23.84,1:09:25.82,Default,,0,0,0,,intoxicated by fleeting prosperity...
Dialogue: 10,1:09:31.83,1:09:37.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Quite right—this country is finished, and it's not only politicians and big businesses that deserve the blame.
Dialogue: 10,1:09:37.40,1:09:40.83,Default,,0,0,0,,This situation stems from the choices we've made ourselves.
Dialogue: 10,1:09:40.83,1:09:42.84,Default,,0,0,0,,We’ve had numerous chances \Nto say “no” until now.
Dialogue: 10,1:09:42.84,1:09:48.58,Default,,0,0,0,,However, our obsession with the prospect of quick gains has caused us to forget what truly matters along the way. {no clue what's misaki here, lit: we were only swayed by misaki's desires, we forgot what we really need somewhere - doesn't seem like there was any premier minister of such name so I'm at a complete loss}
Dialogue: 10,1:09:48.58,1:09:51.38,Default,,0,0,0,,It's them... Without people like them,
Dialogue: 10,1:09:51.95,1:09:53.85,Default,,0,0,0,,the world would be a better place. {lit: like this... people like this might as well die and it'll be good}
Dialogue: 10,1:12:01.25,1:12:02.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Who are you?
Dialogue: 10,1:12:02.35,1:12:06.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Disgusting humans, \Nwho don't even grow their own food,
Dialogue: 10,1:12:06.75,1:12:13.78,Default,,0,0,0,,who destroy the mountains, pollute the sea, \Nand neglect nature—you've brought about your own ruin!
Dialogue: 10,1:12:15.26,1:12:18.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Mountain God, \Nthe other mountain is also collapsing!
Dialogue: 10,1:12:18.90,1:12:20.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Mountain God?
Dialogue: 10,1:12:20.12,1:12:24.37,Default,,0,0,0,,There's no longer any way \Nwe can coexist with these idiotic humans!
Dialogue: 10,1:12:24.37,1:12:27.20,Default,,0,0,0,,It's the end for them and for Japan!
Dialogue: 10,1:12:27.20,1:12:32.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Wait, Mountain God! \NIs there really, really no hope left for us?
Dialogue: 10,1:12:32.11,1:12:33.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it decided already?
Dialogue: 10,1:12:35.35,1:12:36.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Farewell.
Dialogue: 10,1:12:38.47,1:12:41.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Wait! Don’t leave me behind!
Dialogue: 10,1:12:41.37,1:12:44.66,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}{\fade(0,1500)}Wait! Don’t leave me behind!{\i0}
Dialogue: 10,1:12:54.47,1:12:56.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah! The house!
Dialogue: 10,1:12:56.60,1:12:57.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Our house!
Dialogue: 10,1:13:04.83,1:13:08.75,Default,,0,0,0,,No, this is hopeless. \NIt just wouldn't stand straight. {unsure what he means and how it's supposed to work for this crop, or what this crop is, even}
Dialogue: 10,1:13:22.80,1:13:26.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Dad, these are rotten to the core! {unsure its touchan}
Dialogue: 10,1:13:26.43,1:13:27.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah...
Dialogue: 10,1:13:32.02,1:13:37.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Keep the fire burning! \NThe temperature is still dropping!
Dialogue: 10,1:13:49.38,1:13:51.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Please line up!
Dialogue: 10,1:13:51.09,1:13:53.49,Default,,0,0,0,,One full bucket per person!
Dialogue: 10,1:13:53.49,1:13:55.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't be so stingy! {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,1:13:55.43,1:13:58.30,Default,,0,0,0,,One full bucket per person!
Dialogue: 10,1:13:58.30,1:14:02.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, don't jump the line! \NPlease line up! {guess}
Dialogue: 10,1:14:31.80,1:14:34.77,Default,,0,0,0,,What? How is it {\i1}this{\i0} expensive?!
Dialogue: 10,1:14:34.77,1:14:37.66,Default,,0,0,0,,It can't be helped! \NThe weather is bad and the crops are failing.
Dialogue: 10,1:14:38.54,1:14:40.74,Default,,0,0,0,,All the ingredients have hiked in price.
Dialogue: 10,1:14:40.74,1:14:42.36,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll just have miso soup.
Dialogue: 10,1:14:42.36,1:14:46.34,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm sorry, but all soybean imports \Nhave come to a halt.
Dialogue: 10,1:14:49.94,1:14:51.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Please line up!
Dialogue: 10,1:14:51.32,1:14:53.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Only those with rationing tickets!
Dialogue: 10,1:14:53.84,1:14:55.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay, that's all for today!
Dialogue: 10,1:14:55.39,1:14:57.09,Default,,0,0,0,,What do you mean?!
Dialogue: 10,1:15:26.48,1:15:27.52,Default,,0,0,0,,A dream...
Dialogue: 10,1:15:29.91,1:15:36.23,Default,,0,0,0,,No, this isn't just a dream. \NIn a few years, it will be our reality.
Dialogue: 10,1:15:36.23,1:15:39.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And that'll be the end of Japan.
Dialogue: 10,1:15:54.67,1:15:59.12,Default,,0,0,0,,"American Train that carries dreams?" \NDon't make me laugh!
Dialogue: 10,1:16:01.15,1:16:02.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Hello.
Dialogue: 10,1:16:02.52,1:16:05.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, the young lady I met the other day?
Dialogue: 10,1:16:05.02,1:16:06.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Um...
Dialogue: 10,1:16:06.56,1:16:10.93,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't mean to make excuses, \Nbut I wasn't the one who wrote that.
Dialogue: 10,1:16:11.83,1:16:13.18,Default,,0,0,0,,I know.
Dialogue: 10,1:16:13.18,1:16:16.77,Default,,0,0,0,,I never thought you'd write \Nsuch a disgusting article.
Dialogue: 10,1:16:16.77,1:16:20.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, why don’t you stop \Nbeing so shy and take a seat? {actually "not make such a scary face" whatever that means, maybe "I'm not really that scary"}
Dialogue: 10,1:16:20.17,1:16:21.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Sure.
Dialogue: 10,1:16:22.97,1:16:25.36,Default,,0,0,0,,But I still feel guilty.
Dialogue: 10,1:16:25.84,1:16:28.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Ultimately, only subjective articles get approved. {lit: no choice but to write such irresponsible articles}
Dialogue: 10,1:16:28.78,1:16:31.28,Default,,0,0,0,,I nearly feel embarrassed to be in the media. {actually "I'm a member of the media, that's for sure" - no clue what she means}
Dialogue: 10,1:16:31.82,1:16:33.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Hm. Can't argue with that. {/maybe you're right}
Dialogue: 10,1:16:35.52,1:16:36.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Um...
Dialogue: 10,1:16:36.62,1:16:38.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes?
Dialogue: 10,1:16:38.06,1:16:41.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Is Japan done for?
Dialogue: 10,1:16:41.96,1:16:44.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Is there no way to divert it \Nfrom self-destruction?
Dialogue: 10,1:16:45.30,1:16:48.39,Default,,0,0,0,,If things keep going the way they are, \Nits fate is sealed.
Dialogue: 10,1:16:49.10,1:16:51.79,Default,,0,0,0,,So there's no future for us anymore...?
Dialogue: 10,1:16:52.80,1:16:54.66,Default,,0,0,0,,No, there is a future.
Dialogue: 10,1:16:55.11,1:16:56.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh?
Dialogue: 10,1:16:56.91,1:16:59.51,Default,,0,0,0,,No matter how dire the situation becomes,
Dialogue: 10,1:16:59.51,1:17:03.52,Default,,0,0,0,,as long as there are people \Nworking hard everywhere to overcome it,
Dialogue: 10,1:17:03.52,1:17:09.02,Default,,0,0,0,,and even a glimmer of conscience to reflect on the past and seek to make amends, there is hope for the future.
Dialogue: 10,1:17:09.62,1:17:10.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Is that true?
Dialogue: 10,1:17:10.89,1:17:11.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 10,1:17:13.06,1:17:15.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Follow me, I'll show you the future.
Dialogue: 10,1:17:16.43,1:17:17.85,Default,,0,0,0,,The future?
Dialogue: 10,1:17:17.85,1:17:18.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 10,1:17:21.27,1:17:23.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah, wait!
Dialogue: 10,1:17:33.04,1:17:34.68,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the future.
Dialogue: 10,1:17:34.68,1:17:37.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Looks like just an ordinary agricultural plant.
Dialogue: 10,1:17:38.52,1:17:40.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Hard to tell from the looks of it, isn't it? {/doesn't look like future does it}
Dialogue: 10,1:17:41.05,1:17:41.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Y-Yes...
Dialogue: 10,1:17:41.99,1:17:45.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Hm. Well, let me give you a tour, \Nand then you can decide.
Dialogue: 10,1:17:50.88,1:17:54.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Young lady, do you know \Nwhat they are doing?
Dialogue: 10,1:17:54.13,1:17:54.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes...
Dialogue: 10,1:17:54.83,1:17:58.20,Default,,0,0,0,,That's the same as making the soil.
Dialogue: 10,1:17:58.20,1:17:59.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Make soil?
Dialogue: 10,1:18:00.73,1:18:02.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 10,1:18:02.17,1:18:04.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, Gen-san!
Dialogue: 10,1:18:04.91,1:18:06.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, Yamazawa-san?
Dialogue: 10,1:18:06.61,1:18:10.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Could you please teach this young lady \Nhow to make soil?
Dialogue: 10,1:18:10.67,1:18:13.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, it's nothing difficult, really.
Dialogue: 10,1:18:13.55,1:18:18.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Organic farming is all about \Nletting nature take its course. Yah. {lit: leave things to the laws of nature}
Dialogue: 10,1:18:18.46,1:18:20.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Nature's course? {/laws}
Dialogue: 10,1:18:20.02,1:18:24.93,Default,,0,0,0,,What I mean is, crops grow in the fields \Nby absorbing nutrients from the soil. {no clue waht's tsudzu here}
Dialogue: 10,1:18:24.93,1:18:26.86,Default,,0,0,0,,And then the animals eat them. {no clue what's after sore wo, this farmer's tsugaru dialect is killing me}
Dialogue: 10,1:18:26.87,1:18:31.40,Default,,0,0,0,,But crops pull nutrients from the soil, \Nso if left unchecked, the land will soon be depleted.{still no clue what's tsudzu but seems to be some word for soil/earth}
Dialogue: 10,1:18:31.40,1:18:35.87,Default,,0,0,0,,That's why we humans use fertilizer. \NIt nourishes the soil. {no clue what's last part}
Dialogue: 10,1:18:35.87,1:18:39.88,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, we create the humus. Yah.
Dialogue: 10,1:18:39.88,1:18:43.18,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's how we sustain the natural cycle.
Dialogue: 10,1:18:43.18,1:18:48.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Take a look at this. There are billions of microorganisms even in this handful of soil.
Dialogue: 10,1:18:48.89,1:18:51.22,Default,,0,0,0,,What we're doing is breathing life into it. {I don't know waht he says anymore}
Dialogue: 10,1:18:51.22,1:18:52.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Living soil?
Dialogue: 10,1:18:52.62,1:18:54.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, that's what makes
Dialogue: 10,1:18:54.78,1:18:57.13,Default,,0,0,0,,all these crops grow for us. {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,1:18:57.13,1:19:00.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Those are nothing like \Nthe ones churned out in factories. {no clue: we don't make the products that leave the factory}
Dialogue: 10,1:19:00.40,1:19:04.43,Default,,0,0,0,,There are microorganisms \Nand minerals in the soil.
Dialogue: 10,1:19:04.43,1:19:06.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Destroying these is a no-no.
Dialogue: 10,1:19:06.23,1:19:09.97,Default,,0,0,0,,What pesticides and chemical fertilizers do is killing the soil. {deaden}
Dialogue: 10,1:19:09.97,1:19:14.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Usually, you can finish the harvesting cycle in less then 100 days with pesticide farming. {I give up: generally, chemical farming takes at most 100 people - 100 people per what? what's it do with next line? I don't know}
Dialogue: 10,1:19:14.04,1:19:16.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, the natural cycle should be longer. {no clue: sujin (no idea) farming is longer, isn't it? - nagai could only be longer in time/distance so that previous line couldn't be about people but I don't know what else could that 100 be}
Dialogue: 10,1:19:16.75,1:19:22.08,Default,,0,0,0,,That's why we also set up square-shaped compost bins to replenish the soil. Yah. {lit: that's why we do orandabakko, build compost/manure places and kurebe the earth - last time oranda referred to grazing animals so maybe here it's manure}
Dialogue: 10,1:19:22.08,1:19:23.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Compost?
Dialogue: 10,1:19:23.15,1:19:30.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Compost is created by packing and fermenting rice straw, \Ndried grass, and other plant and animal waste.
Dialogue: 10,1:19:30.49,1:19:34.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, mixing that into the ground \Nand watering it makes the soil as good as new. {I didn't get a single word here...}
Dialogue: 10,1:19:34.92,1:19:38.60,Default,,0,0,0,,That also lets you make use \Nof livestock waste and rice straw. {one word I could get was "manure"...}
Dialogue: 10,1:19:38.60,1:19:42.91,Default,,0,0,0,,The rest could be used for chicken feed, \Nand chicken droppings make excellent compost. {one word I got here was "compost"}
Dialogue: 10,1:19:42.91,1:19:46.84,Default,,0,0,0,,It's easy to disrupt the ecosystem if you're not careful with it. {lit: What's more, natural ecosystems are easily destroyed - no clue what he means}
Dialogue: 10,1:19:46.84,1:19:50.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Selling surplus compost can, in turn, \Nbecome a valuable source of income. {only word of the day here is "cash income"}
Dialogue: 10,1:19:50.28,1:19:53.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Work with nature, \Nand it will reward you in return.
Dialogue: 10,1:19:53.75,1:19:56.38,Default,,0,0,0,,That mindset is essential, yah.
Dialogue: 10,1:19:56.38,1:19:58.22,Default,,0,0,0,,We are the producers.
Dialogue: 10,1:19:58.22,1:20:01.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Work with nature \Nand it will reward you back?
Dialogue: 10,1:20:01.19,1:20:03.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, it's really that simple.
Dialogue: 10,1:20:03.74,1:20:07.20,Default,,0,0,0,,All you need is a genuine desire to produce something good. Right, Gen-san? {no idea}
Dialogue: 10,1:20:07.20,1:20:11.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Absolutely! Grow real food and eat real food. That’s all there is to it. {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,1:20:26.08,1:20:31.02,Default,,0,0,0,,The number of farmers like him is gradually increasing across the country.
Dialogue: 10,1:20:31.02,1:20:35.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, we keep in touch and hold study sessions, among other things.
Dialogue: 10,1:20:35.96,1:20:38.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you. \NI caught a glimpse of the future.
Dialogue: 10,1:20:42.63,1:20:45.10,Default,,0,0,0,,This is also future.
Dialogue: 10,1:20:45.10,1:20:46.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Organic farming?
Dialogue: 10,1:20:46.79,1:20:50.01,Default,,0,0,0,,You've learned a lot more now, \Nbut that's not all.
Dialogue: 10,1:20:50.01,1:20:53.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Here, they are restarting rice cultivation \Nfrom the ground up.
Dialogue: 10,1:20:53.91,1:20:54.86,Default,,0,0,0,,From the ground up?
Dialogue: 10,1:20:54.86,1:20:55.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Exactly!
Dialogue: 10,1:20:55.75,1:20:57.31,Default,,0,0,0,,If it isn't Tome-san!
Dialogue: 10,1:20:57.31,1:20:58.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Long time no see.
Dialogue: 10,1:20:58.52,1:21:01.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Well said! Tome-san, please show us \Nthe future of rice cultivation.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:01.64,1:21:02.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Sure.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:02.72,1:21:06.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Japanese rice cultivation has suffered great setbacks over the past 25 years. {they decided to give him SOME FUCKING ACCENT TOO so I still didn't get a single word of that}
Dialogue: 10,1:21:06.65,1:21:12.33,Top,,0,0,0,,Over-mechanization, excessive pesticide use, and mono-cropping have led to a decline in the soil's quality.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:12.33,1:21:13.65,Top,,0,0,0,,After all, those are also
Dialogue: 10,1:21:13.65,1:21:14.88,Top,,0,0,0,,important for our imports. {no clue what's kintan}
Dialogue: 10,1:21:14.88,1:21:18.70,Default,,0,0,0,,For years, we pretended that those are helping both the farmer and the customer. {only hear "how many years, only for farmer and customer"}
Dialogue: 10,1:21:18.70,1:21:20.16,Default,,0,0,0,,So what we did was,
Dialogue: 10,1:21:20.16,1:21:23.51,Default,,0,0,0,,persuading them that the rice farmers are the basis of Japan's food production.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:23.51,1:21:26.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, if you just think about it, \Nit sounds confusing at first. {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,1:21:26.24,1:21:27.44,Default,,0,0,0,,But let's try.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:27.44,1:21:29.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan cultivated rice for thousands of years.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:29.98,1:21:32.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Rice cultivation, namely paddy fields,
Dialogue: 10,1:21:32.52,1:21:34.55,Top,,0,0,0,,was where the Japanese culture was born.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:34.55,1:21:37.82,Top,,0,0,0,,That's not all. Take, for example, \N"Let's build a rice field." {I have no idea what this is about}
Dialogue: 10,1:21:37.82,1:21:40.26,Default,,0,0,0,,It's not just about growing rice.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:40.26,1:21:42.43,Default,,0,0,0,,It is used to say "let's protect our land."
Dialogue: 10,1:21:42.43,1:21:43.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Protect the land?
Dialogue: 10,1:21:43.83,1:21:44.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:44.56,1:21:47.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Tome-san refers to this.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:47.03,1:21:49.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Paddy fields are also a water storage.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:49.07,1:21:52.97,Default,,0,0,0,,In times of flood, they contain the water as well as dams do.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:52.97,1:21:54.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Like dams?
Dialogue: 10,1:21:54.36,1:21:55.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:55.01,1:21:59.01,Default,,0,0,0,,The amount of water stored in Japanese paddy fields is approximately 8.1 billion tons.
Dialogue: 10,1:21:59.01,1:22:03.68,Default,,0,0,0,,This is about three times the amount of water in all the dams in Japan.
Dialogue: 10,1:22:03.68,1:22:08.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Correct. They make the water seep into the ground and become groundwater, also useful for other plants. {no clue what's this da, as well as the rest of the line}
Dialogue: 10,1:22:08.79,1:22:11.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Since ancient times, we covered the mountains in rice fields.
Dialogue: 10,1:22:11.89,1:22:15.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Every farmer understands their usefulness through a close connection with nature.
Dialogue: 10,1:22:15.56,1:22:18.10,Default,,0,0,0,,The forests on the hills \Nalso receive additional water.{not a single word}
Dialogue: 10,1:22:18.10,1:22:21.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Groundwater plays a crucial role in maintaining natural circulation.
Dialogue: 10,1:22:21.30,1:22:24.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Groundwater helps alleviate \Nthe effects of drought.
Dialogue: 10,1:22:24.70,1:22:30.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Forests absorb solar heat and evaporate water, regulate temperature and prevent wind from running rampant. {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,1:22:30.30,1:22:34.85,Default,,0,0,0,,The flash floods and landslides weren't nearly as frequent in the past. {guess}
Dialogue: 10,1:22:34.85,1:22:37.75,Default,,0,0,0,,But we've all but forgotten \Nto appreciate it nowadays. {lit: we're doing environmentally damaging (indiscriminate) development and forgetting the blessing of the mountains and the forests}
Dialogue: 10,1:22:37.75,1:22:41.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Leveling rice fields \Nto build golf courses is reckless!
Dialogue: 10,1:22:41.27,1:22:44.18,Default,,0,0,0,,So we must take an active stance \Nfor a return to the mountains. {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,1:22:44.18,1:22:49.09,Top,,0,0,0,,Rice paddies filled with water shield the nutrient-rich soil from being swept away by the wind. {no clue}
Dialogue: 10,1:22:49.09,1:22:51.26,Top,,0,0,0,,So they're protecting the earth as well.
Dialogue: 10,1:22:51.26,1:22:54.53,Default,,0,0,0,,The greenery of the rice fields also helps provide fresh air.
Dialogue: 10,1:22:54.53,1:22:57.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you really think American and Thai rice will protect Japan's
Dialogue: 10,1:22:57.33,1:22:59.64,Default,,0,0,0,,greenery or take the place of dams? \NWhadja say? {nc what's shinebi}
Dialogue: 10,1:22:59.64,1:23:03.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Unlike conventional fields, \Npaddy fields aren't affected by mono-cropping.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:03.24,1:23:05.54,Default,,0,0,0,,And you can grow wheat as a secondary crop.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:05.54,1:23:08.08,Default,,0,0,0,,But wheat isn't much good \Nfor anything besides milling.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:08.08,1:23:10.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, any excess rice \Ncan easily be used as animal feed.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:10.91,1:23:13.48,Default,,0,0,0,,I want to eliminate pesticide-laden agriculture.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:13.48,1:23:17.09,Default,,0,0,0,,My dad has cancer; \NI’m sure it’s also because of pesticides.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:17.09,1:23:19.51,Default,,0,0,0,,If it kills bugs and weeds, \Nsurely enough, it kill people too.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:19.51,1:23:21.26,Default,,0,0,0,,We'd be better off without it. {not a word}
Dialogue: 10,1:23:21.26,1:23:25.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Debts are increasing because of forced mechanization, \Nand migrant farmers are losing their jobs.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:25.23,1:23:28.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Blinded by subsidies, we've lost sight \Nof the true essence of agriculture and forestry.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:28.80,1:23:31.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Originally, we grew rice \Nby managing the water temperature. {sounds suion pretty clearly, I don't know how this works, can't find any evidence but w/e}
Dialogue: 10,1:23:31.97,1:23:36.04,Default,,0,0,0,,We also began using it as a method \Nto combat pests and diseases.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:36.04,1:23:41.11,Default,,0,0,0,,This means that every rice farmer \Nis a self-sufficient farmer.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:41.11,1:23:45.34,Default,,0,0,0,,These people aspire to become the foundation of this new culture of rice farming.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:45.34,1:23:48.12,Default,,0,0,0,,So you want every farmer to be self-sufficient?
Dialogue: 10,1:23:48.12,1:23:50.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Independent distribution \Nis still a tough challenge, though.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:50.89,1:23:52.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Especially with the new food regulations. {unsure but seems to be "law governing food quality"}
Dialogue: 10,1:23:52.96,1:23:55.61,Default,,0,0,0,,But we, simple farmers, still persevere. {no clue, hear "sukasuma such farmers suddenly kotowatasuka da", could be "suddenly overwhelmed" or "they're trying to suffocate us" or "we keep going"}
Dialogue: 10,1:23:56.26,1:23:58.53,Default,,0,0,0,,You showed me one more future for Japan.
Dialogue: 10,1:23:58.53,1:24:00.93,Default,,0,0,0,,I feel a little better already.
Dialogue: 10,1:24:01.62,1:24:05.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Now then, let me tell you a story \Nthat will cheer you up even more.
Dialogue: 10,1:24:05.57,1:24:07.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, please do.
Dialogue: 10,1:24:18.38,1:24:21.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, here you can see another future.
Dialogue: 10,1:24:21.32,1:24:23.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Grandpa!
Dialogue: 10,1:24:23.82,1:24:26.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, hey there! \NHelping your parents, I see?
Dialogue: 10,1:24:26.98,1:24:28.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah!
Dialogue: 10,1:24:28.09,1:24:29.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah, hello!
Dialogue: 10,1:24:29.15,1:24:29.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Hello.
Dialogue: 10,1:24:29.98,1:24:31.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Is he doing well?
Dialogue: 10,1:24:31.28,1:24:32.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, he's working hard!
Dialogue: 10,1:24:32.83,1:24:36.53,Default,,0,0,0,,But dad still says he's just a layabout. {https://jisho.org/word/%E3%81%B8%E3%81%A3%E3%81%B4%E3%82%8A%E8%85%B0 - neither seems to make a lot of sense here, idk what he means}
Dialogue: 10,1:24:36.53,1:24:38.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Excuse me, who is he talking about?
Dialogue: 10,1:24:38.50,1:24:40.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Him, of course.
Dialogue: 10,1:24:41.14,1:24:43.61,Default,,0,0,0,,You took your sweet time, \Ndidn’t you, Mariko-san? {/you're late, aren't you}
Dialogue: 10,1:24:43.61,1:24:46.06,Default,,0,0,0,,I-Ishida-kun! Why are you here?
Dialogue: 10,1:24:46.06,1:24:49.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Why, gathering material, of course! {that iyadana probably means "come on, you're supposed to know it"}
Dialogue: 10,1:24:49.21,1:24:52.76,Default,,0,0,0,,But lately I've also been \Nhelping people out a lot more. {unsure what he means}
Dialogue: 10,1:24:53.98,1:24:56.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Come on, let me show you the {\i1}future{\i0}!
Dialogue: 10,1:24:57.52,1:25:01.86,Default,,0,0,0,,The products harvested at this farm \Nare delivered directly to consumers.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:01.86,1:25:04.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Consumers also help in transporting the goods.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:04.95,1:25:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,With fewer middlemen involved, the products avoid any added costs.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:09.00,1:25:10.37,Default,,0,0,0,,It's very cheap.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:10.37,1:25:13.24,Default,,0,0,0,,And the products are still fresh \Nwhen they are delivered.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:13.24,1:25:16.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah, and here comes the representative from the consumer group.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:16.77,1:25:17.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Hello.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:17.80,1:25:20.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you always here?
Dialogue: 10,1:25:20.70,1:25:25.62,Default,,0,0,0,,No, not all the time, \Nbut I make an effort to visit whenever I can.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:25.62,1:25:28.65,Default,,0,0,0,,I enjoy meeting the people \Nat the production site.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:29.12,1:25:37.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Firstly, here, producers and consumers can connect, letting us cook and eat with peace of mind.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:37.19,1:25:40.33,Default,,0,0,0,,When I know it’s going to be eaten \Nby an anonymous someone I don’t know,
Dialogue: 10,1:25:40.33,1:25:43.33,Default,,0,0,0,,I end up thinking that as long as it sells, \Nit’s good enough.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:43.33,1:25:48.01,Default,,0,0,0,,People often buy it simply because it looks appealing and is cheap.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:48.01,1:25:48.67,Default,,0,0,0,,That's right.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:49.27,1:25:55.57,Default,,0,0,0,,I believe it’s time for us as consumers \Nto be more conscious about what we eat.
Dialogue: 10,1:25:55.57,1:25:59.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it really all right to just mindlessly consume everything?
Dialogue: 10,1:25:59.52,1:26:04.19,Default,,0,0,0,,They say those vegetables and fruits can last two to three weeks in the refrigerator.
Dialogue: 10,1:26:04.19,1:26:06.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it really safe to eat such products?
Dialogue: 10,1:26:06.12,1:26:11.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Can we really take it for granted that seasonal fruits and vegetables can be eaten year-round?
Dialogue: 10,1:26:11.56,1:26:18.80,Default,,0,0,0,,If we consumers keep consuming carelessly, why wouldn't the producers do the same? {means "produce carelessly"}
Dialogue: 10,1:26:20.39,1:26:22.97,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems we need to reconsider our dietary habits,
Dialogue: 10,1:26:22.97,1:26:28.25,Default,,0,0,0,,which currently focus on being \N"rich, beautiful, and all-you-can-eat year-round."
Dialogue: 10,1:26:28.25,1:26:32.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Both production and consumption should align with nature.
Dialogue: 10,1:26:32.08,1:26:36.22,Default,,0,0,0,,It's up to humans to rebuild the nature \Nthat they have destroyed.
Dialogue: 10,1:26:36.22,1:26:41.75,Default,,0,0,0,,We believe that living in harmony with nature is the key to true happiness for humanity.
Dialogue: 10,1:26:41.75,1:26:43.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, I understand.
Dialogue: 10,1:26:44.13,1:26:47.50,Default,,0,0,0,,All across the country, farmers, rural areas,
Dialogue: 10,1:26:47.50,1:26:53.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and consumer groups like our friend here that embrace this mindset are slowly gaining traction.
Dialogue: 10,1:26:53.63,1:26:57.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh my, Ishida-kun, you're beginning to sound \Nlike one of the farmers yourself! {hope she means this}
Dialogue: 10,1:26:57.53,1:26:58.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Huh?
Dialogue: 10,1:26:59.43,1:27:06.55,Default,,0,0,0,,By working with the producers, lobbying the government, \Nand expanding the circle of our groups,
Dialogue: 10,1:27:06.55,1:27:10.54,Default,,0,0,0,,we've been making steady progress, although still little by little.
Dialogue: 10,1:27:11.15,1:27:18.73,Default,,0,0,0,,The drive to make and eat only real food \Nis still very strong in people.
Dialogue: 10,1:27:18.73,1:27:22.63,Default,,0,0,0,,What do you say, young lady? \NWon't you lend us a hand?
Dialogue: 10,1:27:22.63,1:27:23.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Huh?
Dialogue: 10,1:27:24.56,1:27:28.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Although the number of people who understand is growing,
Dialogue: 10,1:27:28.41,1:27:30.46,Default,,0,0,0,,we are still just a small speck
Dialogue: 10,1:27:30.46,1:27:32.64,Default,,0,0,0,,scattered across the country.
Dialogue: 10,1:27:32.64,1:27:37.18,Default,,0,0,0,,That's where people like you \Nand Ishida-kun come in. {/what you and ishida are needed for}
Dialogue: 10,1:27:37.18,1:27:41.05,Default,,0,0,0,,I understand. I will be happy to help.
Dialogue: 10,1:27:41.05,1:27:43.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Actually, I would be honored to. {lit: I should've been asking you to let me help you}
Dialogue: 10,1:27:43.92,1:27:47.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Just a little while ago, \NI felt so powerless it made me nauseous.
Dialogue: 10,1:27:47.59,1:27:50.82,Default,,0,0,0,,But now, I can clearly \Nsee the future with my own eyes.
Dialogue: 10,1:27:56.77,1:27:58.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, lady!
Dialogue: 10,1:27:59.37,1:28:02.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Lady, please eat this tomato! \NI grew it myself.
Dialogue: 10,1:28:02.49,1:28:04.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you!
Dialogue: 10,1:28:04.27,1:28:06.78,Default,,0,0,0,,His tomatoes really are something else.
Dialogue: 10,1:28:11.35,1:28:12.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Wow, it's so good!
Dialogue: 10,1:28:12.92,1:28:15.12,Default,,0,0,0,,It has thick flesh and a strong aroma!
Dialogue: 10,1:28:15.62,1:28:19.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Now I realize that the tomatoes I've been eating until now weren't the real deal.
Dialogue: 10,1:28:19.34,1:28:23.79,Default,,0,0,0,,We've finally found something \Nwe can eat without worry.
Dialogue: 10,1:28:23.79,1:28:25.76,Default,,0,0,0,,You're absolutely right!
Dialogue: 10,1:28:25.76,1:28:28.19,Default,,0,0,0,,But it's still a long way to go...
Dialogue: 10,1:28:50.71,1:28:52.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Mountain God!
Dialogue: 10,1:28:55.56,1:28:58.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you back to normal, Mountain God? {act. "you've returned, haven't you" so maybe "you've returned to us"}
Dialogue: 10,1:29:21.51,1:29:26.76,Thought,,0,0,0,,It's up to us to rebuild \Nthe nature we've destroyed.
Dialogue: 10,1:29:27.59,1:29:29.39,Thought,,0,0,0,,To calm the land's anger, {movie title}
Dialogue: 10,1:29:29.39,1:29:33.76,Thought,,0,0,0,,to regain the lifestyle where humans live in harmony with nature...
Dialogue: 10,1:29:33.76,1:29:37.73,Thought,,0,0,0,,Our journey only begins now.
